    <h2>
      CHAPTER X
    </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">A</span> fortnight passed.
      Yvonne held the destiny of three persons in her hand. They were like
      figures on a chess-board, and she moved them with the sureness, the
      unerring instinct of any skilled disciple of the philosopher's game. They
      were puppets; she ranged them about her stage in swift-changing pictures,
      and applauded her own effectiveness. There were no rehearsals. The play
      was going on all the time, whether tragedy, comedy, or chess.
    </p>
    <p>
      Brood's uneasiness increased. His moody eyes were seldom lifted to meet
      the question that he knew lurked in hers. She had given him a tremendous
      shock. There was seldom a moment in which he was not making strange
      inquiries of himself.
    </p>
    <p>
      Was it possible that she had spoken the truth about him? Could such a
      condition of mind exist without his knowledge? Was this love he professed
      to feel for her but the flame springing into life from those despised
      embers of long ago? Was it true that his inner self, his subconscious
      being, recognised no other claim to his love than the one held so
      insecurely by its original possessor? Was it true that his soul went back
      to her the instant slumber came to close up the gap of years?
    </p>
    <p>
      This strange, new wife of his had uttered amazing words; she had spoken
      without rancour; she had called his dreams to life; she had told him how
      he lived while asleep!
    </p>
    <p>
      He arose in the mornings, haggard from lack of reposeful sleep. In a way,
      he slept with one ear open, constantly striving to catch himself with the
      dream-name on his lips. He would awake with a start many times in the
      night, and always there seemed to be the vague, ghostlike whisper of a
      name dying away in the stillness that greeted his return to wakefulness.
    </p>
    <p>
      Now he confessed to himself that his dreams were of Matilde, as they had
      been during all the years. Heretofore they had been mere impressions upon
      his intelligence, and seldom remembered. They did not represent pictures
      or incidents in which she appeared as a potent factor, but brief monodies,
      with her name as the single note, her face a passing, yet impressive,
      vision. He had not realised how frequent, how real these dreams were until
      now.
    </p>
    <p>
      He sometimes lay perfectly still after these awakenings, wondering if
      Yvonne was listening at his closed door, straining his ears for the sound
      of a creaking board that would betray her presence as she stole back to
      her own bed.
    </p>
    <p>
      What surprised and puzzled him most was her serenity in the face of these
      involuntary revelations. She did not appear to be disturbed by the fact
      that his dreams, his most secret thoughts, were of another woman. There
      was nothing in her manner to indicate that she suffered any of the pangs
      of jealousy, humiliation, dismay, or doubt that might reasonably have been
      expected under the circumstances. She seemed to put the matter entirely
      out of her mind as trivial, unimportant, unvexing. He found himself
      wondering what his own state of mind would be if the conditions were
      reversed and it was she who cried out in her sleep.
    </p>
    <p>
      Frederic was alert, shifty, secretive. He knew himself to be the link in
      the chain that would offer the least resistance of any if it came to the
      question of endurance. He realised that the slightest tug at the chain
      would cause it to snap, and that the break would never be repaired. His
      stepmother for the present fortified the weak spot in the chain; but would
      her strength be sufficient to support the strain that was to be imposed
      upon both links in the end?
    </p>
    <p>
      He watched her like a hawk, ever on the lookout for the slightest signs of
      commendation, reproof, warning, encouragement. She alone stood between him
      and what appeared to be the inevitable. The truce was a mask that hid none
      of the real features of the situation. When would it be discarded?
    </p>
    <p>
      After that illuminating hour in her boudoir he saw himself in a far from
      noble position. The situation was no longer indefinite. He had taken a
      step that could not be recalled. His loyalty to Lydia had been tested, and
      the sickening truth came out&mdash;he was a traitor! He knew in his soul
      that he loved the girl. His conscience told him so. But his conscience
      suddenly had become an elastic thing that stretched over a pretty wide
      scope of emotions. These he tried to analyse and, failing to do so with
      credit to himself, settled back into a state of apathy better described as
      sullen self-pity. He even went so far as to blame his father for the new
      blight that had been put upon him.
    </p>
    <p>
      Of the three, Lydia alone faced the situation with courage. She was young,
      she was good, she was inexperienced, but she saw what was going on beneath
      the surface with a clarity of vision that would have surprised an older
      and more practised person; and, seeing, was favoured with the strength to
      endure pain that otherwise would have been insupportable.
    </p>
    <p>
      She knew that Frederic was infatuated. She did not try to hide the truth
      from herself. The boy she loved was slipping away from her, and only
      chance could set his feet back in the old path from which he blindly
      strayed. Her woman's heart told her that it was not love he felt for
      Yvonne. The strange mentor that guides her sex out of the ignorance of
      youth into an understanding of hitherto unpresented questions revealed to
      her the nature of his feeling for this woman.
    </p>
    <p>
      He would come back to her in time, she knew, chastened; the same instinct
      that revealed his frailties to her also defended his sense of honour. The
      unthinkable could never happen!
    </p>
    <p>
      She judged Yvonne, too, in a spirit of fairness that was amazing,
      considering the lack of perspective that must have been hers to contend
      with. Despite a natural feeling of antagonism, present even before she saw
      the new wife of James Brood, and long before her influence affected
      Brood's son, Lydia found herself confronted by a curious faith in Yvonne's
      goodness of heart. It never entered the girl's mind to question the honour
      of this woman&mdash;no more than she would have questioned her own.
    </p>
    <p>
      Vanity, love of admiration, the inherent fear of retrogression, greed for
      attention&mdash;any one of these might have been responsible for her
      conduct covering the past three months. There was certainly a reckless
      disregard for consequences on her part so far as others&mdash;notably
      Frederic&mdash;were concerned. She could not be blind to his plight, and
      yet it was her pleasure to drag him out beyond his depth where he might
      struggle or drown while she, sirenlike, looked on for the moment and then
      turned calmly to the more serious business of combing her hair.
    </p>
    <p>
      Her mother saw the suffering in the girl's eyes, but saw also the proud
      spirit that would have resented sympathy from one even so close as she.
      Down in the heart of that quiet, reserved mother smouldered a hatred for
      Yvonne Brood that would have stopped at nothing had it been in her power
      to inflict punishment for the wrong that was being done. She, too, saw
      tragedy ahead, but her vision was broader than Lydia's. It included the
      figure of James Brood.
    </p>
    <p>
      Lydia worked steadily, almost doggedly, at the task she had undertaken to
      complete for the elder Brood. Every afternoon found her seated at the desk
      in the study opposite the stern-faced man who laboured with her over the
      seemingly endless story of his life. Something told her that there were
      secret chapters which she was not to write. She wrote those that were to
      endure; the others were to die with him.
    </p>
    <p>
      He watched her as she wrote, and his eyes were often hard. He saw the
      growing haggardness in her gentle, girlish face; the wistful, puzzled
      expression in her dark eyes. A note of tenderness crept into his voice and
      remained there through all the hours they spent together. The old-time
      brusqueness disappeared from his speech; the sharp, authoritative tone was
      gone. He watched her with pity in his heart, for he knew it was ordained
      that one day he, too, was to hurt this loyal, pure-hearted creature even
      as the others were wounding her now.
    </p>
    <p>
      He frequently went out of his way to perform quaint little acts of
      courtesy and kindness that would have surprised him only a short time
      before. He sent theatre and opera tickets to Lydia and her mother. He
      placed bouquets of flowers at the girl's end of the desk, obviously for
      her alone. He sent her home&mdash;just around the corner&mdash;in the
      automobile on rainy or blizzardy days.
    </p>
    <p>
      But he never allowed her an instant's rest when it came to the work in
      hand, and therein lay the gentle shrewdness of the man. She was better off
      busy. There were times when he studied the face of Lydia's mother for
      signs that might show how her thoughts ran in relation to the conditions
      that were confronting all of them. But more often he searched the features
      of the boy who called him father.
    </p>
    <p>
      Not one of them knew that there were solemn hours in all the days when
      Yvonne sat shivering in her room and stared, dry-eyed and bleak, at the
      walls which surrounded her, seeing not them, but something far beyond.
      Often she sat before her long cheval-glass, either with lowering eyes or
      in a sort of wistful wonder, never removing her steady gaze from the face
      reflected there. There were other times when she stood before the striking
      photograph of her husband on the dressing-table, studying the face through
      narrowed lids, as if she searched for something that baffled, yet
      impressed her.
    </p>
    <p>
      Always, always there was music in the house. Behind the closed doors of
      his distant study James Brood listened in spite of himself to the
      persistent thrumming of the piano downstairs. Always were the airs light
      and seductive; the dreamy, plaintive compositions of Strauss, Ziehrer, and
      others of their kind and place.
    </p>
    <p>
      Frederic, with uncanny fidelity to the preferences of the mother he had
      never seen, but whose influence directed him, affected the same general
      class of music that had appealed to her moods and temperament. Times there
      were, and often, when he played the very airs that she had loved, and
      then, despite his profound antipathy, James Brood's thoughts leaped back a
      quarter of a century and fixed themselves on love-scenes and love-times
      that would not be denied.
    </p>
    <p>
      And again there were the wild, riotous airs that she had played with
      Feverelli, her soft-eyed music-master! Accursed airs&mdash;accursed and
      accusing!
    </p>
    <p>
      He gave orders that these airs were not to be played, but failed to make
      his command convincing for the reason that he could not bring himself to
      the point of explaining why they were distasteful to him. When Frederic
      thoughtlessly whistled or hummed fragments of those proscribed airs he
      considered himself justified in commanding him to stop on the pretext that
      they were disturbing, but he could not use the same excuse for checking
      the song on the lips of his gay and impulsive wife. Sometimes he wondered
      why she persisted when she knew that he was annoyed. Her airy little
      apologies for her forgetfulness were of no consequence, for within the
      hour her memory was almost sure to be at fault again.
    </p>
    <p>
      Mr Dawes fell ill. He ventured out one day when the winds of March were
      fierce and sharp, and, being an adventurer, caught the most dangerous sort
      of a cold. He came in shivering and considerably annoyed because Jones or
      Ranjab or some other incompetent servant had failed to advise him to wear
      an overcoat and galoshes. To his surprise Mrs Brood ordered a huge, hot
      drink of whisky and commanded him to drink it&mdash;&ldquo;like a good boy.&rdquo; Then she
      had him stowed away in bed with loads of blankets about him.
    </p>
    <p>
      Just before dinner she came up to see him. He was still shivering. So was
      Mr Riggs, for that matter, but Mr Riggs failed to shiver convincingly and
      did not receive the treatment he desired. Their unexpected visitor felt
      the pulse and forehead of the sick man, uttered a husky little cry of
      dismay, and announced that he had a fever. Whereupon Mr Dawes said, rather
      shamefacedly, that he would be all right in the morning and that it was
      nothing at all.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We will have the doctor at once, Mr Dawes,&rdquo; said she, and instructed Mr
      Riggs to call Jones.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I don't want a doctor,&rdquo; said Mr Dawes stoutly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I know you don't,&rdquo; said she, with her rarest smile; &ldquo;but I <i>do</i>, you
      see.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;They're no good,&rdquo; said Mr Dawes.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Better have one,&rdquo; advised Mr Riggs with sudden solemnity.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Never had one in my life,&rdquo; said Mr Dawes. &ldquo;Don't believe in 'em. I'll
      take a couple of stiff drinks before I go to bed and&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But you've gone to bed, you old dear,&rdquo; cried she, stroking his burning
      hand gently.
    </p>
    <p>
      He was too astonished to say a word.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Jumping Jees&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo; began Mr Riggs, completely staggered. &ldquo;I
      mean, what doctor, Mrs Brood?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Jones will know. Now, Mr Dawes, you must do just as I tell you to do. You
      are nothing but a child, you know. If&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Hey, Joe!&rdquo; called out the sick man desperately, but his comrade was gone.
      &ldquo;Don't let him call a&mdash;doctor, Mrs Brood; please don't!&rdquo; he implored.
    </p>
    <p>
      She sat down on the edge of the bed, holding his hand between her soft,
      cool palms, and smiled at him so tenderly that he stared for a moment in
      utter bewilderment and then gulped mightily. &ldquo;Hush!&rdquo; she said.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&mdash;I don't want to be sick here, bothering you and upsetting
      everything&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo; he blubbered.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We will have you up and about in a day or two,&rdquo; she said.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But it's such an infernal nuisance. You oughtn't to be sitting here,
      either. It may be catching.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nonsense! I'm not afraid.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It's&mdash;it's mighty good of you,&rdquo; he muttered, his eyes blinking.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What are friends for, Mr Dawes, if they can't be depended upon in times
      of sickness?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Friends?&rdquo; he gasped.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Certainly. Am I not your friend?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&mdash;I&mdash;well, by gosh!&rdquo; he exploded. &ldquo;I&mdash;I must tell this to
      Joe. He'll&mdash;I beg your pardon, I guess I'm a little flighty. Maybe
      I'm worse than I think. Delirious or something like that. Say, you don't
      think it's&mdash;it's serious, do you?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Of course not. A heavy cold, that's all. The doctor will break it up
      immediately.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Maybe it's the grippe, eh?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Possibly.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What's my temperature?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You mustn't worry, Mr Dawes. It's all right.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He was silent for a moment, steadfastly regarding the hand that stroked
      his wrinkled old paw so gently.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;If&mdash;if it should turn out to be pneumonia or lung fever, I wish you
      wouldn't let on to Joe,&rdquo; said he anxiously. &ldquo;It would worry him almost to
      death. He's not very strong, you see. Nothing like me. I'm as strong as a
      bull. Never been sick in my&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I know,&rdquo; she said quietly. &ldquo;He isn't half so strong as you, Mr Dawes. You
      are so strong you will be able to throw off this cold in a jiffy, as Jones
      would say. It won't amount to anything.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;If I get much worse you'd better send me to a hospital. Awful nuisance
      having a sick man about the place. Spoils everything. Don't hesitate about
      sending me off, Mrs Brood. I wouldn't be a trouble to you or Jim for&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You poor old dear! You shall stay right where you are, no matter what
      comes to pass, and I shall take charge of you myself.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You?&rdquo; She nodded her head briskly. &ldquo;Well, by jiggers, I&mdash;I don't
      know what Joe'll say when I tell him this. Blast him; I'll bet my head he
      calls me a liar. If he does, blast him, I'll&mdash;oh, I beg your pardon! I
      don't seem to be able to get over the habit of&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Here is Mr Riggs&mdash;and my husband,&rdquo; she interrupted, as the door
      opened and the two men strode into the room. &ldquo;Is Jones telephoning?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes,&rdquo; said Brood. &ldquo;Why, what's gone wrong, old man?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It's all my fault,&rdquo; groaned Mr Riggs, sitting down heavily on the
      opposite side of the bed. &ldquo;I let him go out without his overcoat. He's not
      a strong man, Jim. Least breath of air goes right through&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;See here, Riggs, you know better than that,&rdquo; roared the sick man
      wrathfully. &ldquo;I can stand more&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;There, there!&rdquo; cried Mrs Brood reprovingly. &ldquo;It isn't fair to quarrel
      with Mr Riggs. He can't very well abuse you in return, Mr Dawes, can he?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You may be on your death-bed,&rdquo; said Mr Riggs mournfully, as if that were
      reason enough for not abusing him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nonsense,&rdquo; said Brood; but it was an anxious look that he shot at Yvonne.
      Mr Dawes's face was fiery hot.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I shall come back to see you immediately after dinner, Mr Dawes,&rdquo; said
      she, and again stroked his hand.
    </p>
    <p>
      The two old men stared after her rather blankly as she left the room. They
      couldn't believe their ears.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;She says she'll look after me herself,&rdquo; murmured Mr Dawes hazily. Mr
      Riggs tucked the covers about his chin. &ldquo;Don't do that, Joe! Leave things
      alone, darn you. She fixed 'em as they ought to be.&rdquo; Mr Riggs obediently
      undid his work. &ldquo;That's right. Now don't you do anything without askin'
      her, d'ye hear?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I was only trying to make you&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, don't do it. Leave everything to her.&rdquo; The upshot of it all was
      that Mr Dawes came near to dying. Pneumonia set in at once, and for many
      days he fought what appeared to be a losing fight. Then came the splendid
      days of convalescence, the happiest days of his life. The amazing Mrs
      Brood did &ldquo;look after him.&rdquo; Nurses there were, of course, and doctors in
      consultation, but it was the much-berated mistress of the house who
      &ldquo;pulled him through,&rdquo; as he afterward and always declared in acrimonious
      disputes with Mr Riggs who, while secretly blessing the wife of Brood,
      could not be driven into an open admission that she had done &ldquo;anything
      more than anybody else would have done under the circumstances,&rdquo;&mdash;and
      not &ldquo;half as much, for that matter, as he could have done had he been
      given a chance.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      It may be well to observe here that Mr Riggs was of no earthly use
      whatever during the trying days. Indeed, he gave up hope the instant the
      doctor said &ldquo;pneumonia,&rdquo; and went about the house saying &ldquo;My God&rdquo; to
      himself and everybody else in sepulchral whispers, all the while urging
      Heaven to &ldquo;please do something.&rdquo; He was too pathetic for words.
    </p>
    <p>
      A new and totally unsuspected element in Yvonne's make-up came to light at
      this troublous period. She forsook many pleasures, many comforts in her
      eagerness to help the suffering old man who, she must have known, in his
      heart had long despised her. She did not interfere with the nurses, yet
      made herself so indispensable to old Mr Dawes in the capacity of &ldquo;visiting
      angel&rdquo; that his heart overflowed with gratitude and love. Even when death
      hung directly above his almost sightless eyes he saw her smile of
      encouragement in the shadows, and his spirit responded with what might
      justly have been called the battle-cry of life.
    </p>
    <p>
      To Brood this new side to Yvonne's far from understandable character was
      most gratifying. Seeing her in the rle of good Samaritan was not so
      surprising to him as the real, unaffected sincerity with which she
      ministered to the wants of the querulous old man.
    </p>
    <p>
      Even the nurses, habitually opposed to the good offices of &ldquo;the family,&rdquo;
       were won over by this woman whose unparalleled sweetness levelled them
      into a condition of respect and love that surprised not only themselves
      but the doctors. They were quite docile from the start, and seldom, if
      ever, spoke of Mr Dawes as &ldquo;the patient&rdquo; or of his state as &ldquo;the case.&rdquo;
       They got into the habit of alluding to him as the &ldquo;dear old man,&rdquo; and
      somehow envied each other the hours &ldquo;on duty.&rdquo; They were never sour.
    </p>
    <p>
      And so, when it came time for Mr Dawes to thank the Lord for his escape,
      he refused to commit himself to anything so ridiculous! He even went so
      far as to declare that the doctor had nothing to do with it, a statement
      which rather staggered the nurses.
    </p>
    <p>
      For hours Yvonne read to the blissful old chap. Sometimes she read to him
      in French, again in Russian, and occasionally in German. It was all one to
      him. He did not understand a word of it, but he was happy. He felt
      surprisingly young.
    </p>
    <p>
      She gave up a month to him and he was prepared to give up his life to her.
      To his utter amazement, however, she did not exact anything so valuable as
      that. Indeed, when his recovery was quite complete, she calmly forgot his
      existence and he sank back into the oblivion from which calamity had
      dragged him; sank back to the unhappy level of Mr Riggs and all the others
      who failed to interest her; and there he dreamed of exalted days when she
      wanted him to live, contrasting them with these days in which he might
      just as well be dead for all she seemed to care! He was one of the &ldquo;old
      men&rdquo; again.
    </p>
    <p>
      Mr Riggs, writhing with jealousy, repeatedly remarked, &ldquo;I told you so,&rdquo;
       and somehow felt revenged for the insolent orders she had given to Jones,
      depriving him of the right to even approach the door of the room in which
      his lifelong friend was dying. It had been a hard week for Mr Riggs. He
      hated her as he had never hated anyone in his life before. And yet he
      thanked God for her, and would have died for her! Nothing, nothing in the
      world would have given him more pleasure than to be critically ill for
      her!
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <a name="link2HCH0011" id="link2HCH0011"> </a>
    </p>
    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER XI
    </h2>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Is there anything wrong with my hair, Mr Brood?&rdquo; asked Lydia, with a
      nervous little laugh.
    </p>
    <p>
      They were in the study, and it was ten o'clock of a wet night in April. Of
      late he had required her to spend the evenings with him in a strenuous
      effort to complete the final chapters of the journal. The illness of Mr
      Dawes had interrupted the work, and he was now in a fever of impatience to
      make up for the lost time. He had declared his intention to go abroad with
      his wife as soon as the manuscript was completed. The editor of a
      magazine, a personal friend, had signified his willingness to edit the
      journal and to put it into shape for publication during the summer months,
      against Brood's return in the fall of the year.
    </p>
    <p>
      The master of the house spared neither himself nor Lydia in these last few
      weeks. He wanted to clear up everything before he went away. Lydia's
      willingness to devote the extra hours to his enterprise would have pleased
      him vastly if he had not been afflicted by the same sense of unrest and
      uneasiness that made incessant labour a boon to her as well as to him.
    </p>
    <p>
      Her query followed a long period of silence on his part. He had been
      suggesting alterations in her notes as she read them to him, and there
      were frequent lulls when she made the changes as directed. Without looking
      at him she felt, rather than knew, that he was regarding her fixedly from
      his position opposite. The scrutiny was disturbing to her. She hazarded
      the question for want of a better means of breaking the spell. Of late he
      had taken to watching her with moody interest. She knew that he was
      mentally commenting on the changes he could not help observing in her
      appearance and her manners. This intense, though perhaps unconscious,
      scrutiny annoyed her. Her face was flushed with embarrassment, her heart
      was beating with undue rapidity.
    </p>
    <p>
      Brood started guiltily.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Your hair?&rdquo; he exclaimed. &ldquo;Oh, I see. You women always feel that
      something is wrong with it. I was thinking of something else, however.
      Forgive my stupidity. We can't afford to waste time in thinking, you know,
      and I am a pretty bad offender. It's nearly half-past ten. We've been hard
      at it since eight o'clock. Time to knock off. I will walk around to your
      apartment with you, my dear. It looks like an all-night rain.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He went up to the window and pulled the curtains aside. Her eyes followed
      him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It's such a short distance, Mr Brood,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;I am not afraid to go
      alone.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He was staring down into the court, his fingers grasping the curtains in a
      rigid grip. He did not reply.
    </p>
    <p>
      There was a light in the windows opening out upon Yvonne's balcony.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I fancy Frederic has come in from the concert,&rdquo; he said slowly. &ldquo;He will
      take you home, Lydia. You'd like that better, eh?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He turned toward her, and she paused in the nervous collecting of her
      papers. His eyes were as hard as steel, his lips were set.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Please don't ask Frederic to&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo; she began hurriedly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;They must have left early,&rdquo; he muttered, glancing at his watch. Returning
      to the table he struck the big, melodious gong a couple of sharp blows.
      For the first time in her recollection it sounded a jangling, discordant
      note, as of impatience.
    </p>
    <p>
      She felt her heart sink; an oppressing sense of alarm came over her.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Good night, Mr Brood. Don't think of coming home with&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Wait, Frederic will go with you.&rdquo; It was a command. Ranjab appeared in
      the doorway. &ldquo;Have Mrs Brood and Mr Frederic returned, Ranjab?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, <i>sahib</i>. At ten o'clock.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;If Mr Frederic is in his room, send him to me.&rdquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He is not in his room, <i>sahib</i>.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The two, master and man, looked at each other steadily for a moment.
      Something passed between them.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Tell him that Miss Desmond is ready to go home.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, <i>sahib</i>.&rdquo; The curtains fell.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I prefer to go home alone, Mr Brood,&rdquo; said Lydia, her eyes flashing. &ldquo;Why
      did you send&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And why not?&rdquo; he demanded harshly. She winced, and he was at once sorry.
      &ldquo;Forgive me. I am tired and&mdash;a bit nervous. And you, too, are tired.
      You've been working too steadily at this miserable job, my dear child.
      Thank Heaven, it will soon be over. Pray sit down. Frederic will soon be
      here.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am not tired,&rdquo; she protested stubbornly. &ldquo;I love the work. You don't
      know how proud I shall be when it comes out, and&mdash;and I realise that
      I helped in its making. No one has ever been in a position to tell the
      story of Tibet as you have told it, Mr Brood. Those chapters will make
      history. I&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Your poor father's share in those explorations is what really makes the
      work valuable, my dear. Without his notes and letters I should have been
      feeble indeed.&rdquo; He looked at his watch. &ldquo;They were at the concert, you
      know&mdash;the Hungarian orchestra. A recent importation, 'Tzigane's'
      music. Gipsies.&rdquo; His sentences as well as his thoughts were staccato,
      disconnected.
    </p>
    <p>
      Lydia turned very cold. She dreaded the scene that now seemed unavoidable.
      Frederic would come in response to his father's command, and then&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;
    </p>
    <p>
      Someone began to play upon the piano downstairs. She knew, and he knew,
      that it was Frederic who played. For a long time they listened. The air,
      no doubt, was one he had heard during the evening, a soft, sensuous waltz
      that she had never heard before. The girl's eyes were upon Brood's face.
      It was like a graven image.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;God!&rdquo; fell from his stiff lips. Suddenly he turned upon the girl. &ldquo;Do you
      know what he is playing?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No,&rdquo; she said, scarcely above a whisper.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It was played in this house by its composer before Frederic was born. It
      was played here on the night of his birth, as it had been played many
      times before. It was written by a man named Feverelli. Have you heard of
      him?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Never,&rdquo; she murmured, and shrank, frightened by the deathlike pallor in
      the man's face, by the strange calm in his voice. The gates were being
      opened at last! She saw the thing that was to stalk forth. She would have
      closed her ears against the revelations it carried. &ldquo;Mother will be
      worried if I am not at home&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Guido Feverelli. An Italian born in Hungary. Budapest, that was his home,
      but he professed to be a gipsy. Yes, he wrote the devilish thing. He
      played it a thousand times in that room down&mdash;&mdash;&mdash; And now
      Frederic plays it, after all these years. It is his heritage. God, how I
      hate the thing! Ranjab! Where is the fellow? He must stop the accursed
      thing. He&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Mr Brood! Mr Brood!&rdquo; cried Lydia, appalled. She began to edge toward the
      door.
    </p>
    <p>
      By a mighty effort Brood regained control of himself. He sank into a
      chair, motioning for her to remain. The music had ceased abruptly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He will be here in a moment,&rdquo; said Brood. &ldquo;Don't go.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      They waited, listening. Ranjab entered the room; so noiseless was his
      approach that neither heard his footsteps.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well?&rdquo; demanded Brood, looking beyond.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Master Frederic begs a few minutes' time, <i>sahib</i>. He is putting
      down on paper the music, so that he may not forget. He writes the notes,
      <i>sahib. Madame</i> assists.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Brood's shoulders sagged. His head was bent, but his gaze never left the
      face of the Hindu.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You may go, Ranjab,&rdquo; he said slowly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ten minutes he asks for, <i>sahib</i>, that is all.&rdquo; The curtains fell
      behind him once more.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;So that he may not forget!&rdquo; fell from Brood's lips. He was looking at the
      girl, but did not address his words to her. &ldquo;So that he may not forget! So
      that I, too, may not forget!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Suddenly he arose and confronted the serene image of the Buddha. For a
      full minute he stood there with his hands clasped, his lips moving as if
      in prayer. No sound came from them.
    </p>
    <p>
      The girl remained transfixed, powerless to move. Not until he turned
      toward her and spoke was the spell broken. Then she came quickly to his
      side. He had pronounced her name.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You are about to tell me something, Mr Brood,&rdquo; she cried in great
      agitation. &ldquo;I do not care to listen. I feel that it is something I should
      not know. Please let me go now. I&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He laid his hands upon her shoulders, holding her off at arm's length.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am very fond of you, Lydia. I do not want to hurt you. Sooner would I
      have my tongue cut out than it should wound you by a single word. Yet I
      must speak. You love Frederic. Is not that true?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She returned his gaze unwaveringly. Her face was very white.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, Mr Brood.&rdquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I have known it for some time, although I was the last to see. You love
      him, and you are just beginning to realise that he is not worthy.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Mr Brood!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Your eyes have been opened.&rdquo; She stared, speechless. &ldquo;My poor girl, he
      was born to prove that honest love is the rarest thing in all this world.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, I beg of you, Mr Brood, don't&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It is better that we should talk it over. We have ten minutes. No doubt
      he has told you that he loves you. He is a lovable boy, he is the kind one
      <i>must</i> love. But it is not in his power to love nobly. He loves
      lightly as&rdquo;&mdash;he hesitated, and then went on harshly&mdash;&ldquo;as his
      father before him loved.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Anger dulled her understanding; she did not grasp the full meaning of his
      declaration. Her honest heart rose to the defence of Frederic.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Mr Brood, I do care for Frederic,&rdquo; she flamed, standing very erect before
      him. &ldquo;He is not himself, he has not been himself since she came here. Oh,
      I am fully aware of what I am saying. He is not to be blamed for this
      thing that has happened to him. No one is to blame. It had to be. I can
      wait, Mr Brood. Frederic loves me. I know he does. He will come back to
      me. You have no right to say that he loves lightly, ignobly. You do not
      know him as I know him. You have never tried to know him, never wanted to
      know him. You&mdash;oh, I beg your pardon, Mr Brood. I&mdash;I am
      forgetting myself.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am afraid you do not understand yourself, Lydia,&rdquo; said he levelly. &ldquo;You
      are young, you are trusting. Your lesson will cost you a great deal, my
      dear.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You are mistaken. I do understand myself,&rdquo; she said gravely. &ldquo;May I speak
      plainly, Mr Brood?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Certainly. I intend to speak plainly to you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Frederic loves me. He does not love Yvonne. He is fascinated, as I also
      am fascinated by her, and you, too, Mr Brood. The spell has fallen over
      all of us. Let me go on, please. You say that Frederic loves like his
      father before him. That is true. He loves but one woman. You love but one
      woman, and she is dead. You will always love her. Frederic is like you. He
      loves Yvonne as you do&mdash;oh, I know it hurts! She cast her spell over you,
      why not over him? Is he stronger than you? Is it strange that she should
      attract him as she attracted you? You glory in her beauty, her charm, her
      perfect loveliness, and yet you love&mdash;yes, <i>love</i>, Mr Brood&mdash;the
      woman who was Frederic's mother. Do I make my meaning plain? Well, so it
      is that Frederic loves me. I am content to wait. I know he loves me.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Through all this Brood stared at her in sheer astonishment. He had no
      feeling of anger, no resentment, no thought of protest.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You&mdash;you astound me, Lydia. Is this your own impression, or has it
      been suggested to you by&mdash;by another?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am only agreeing with you when you say that he loves as his father
      loved before him&mdash;but not lightly. Ah, not lightly, Mr Brood.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You don't know what you are saying,&rdquo; he muttered.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, yes, I do,&rdquo; she cried earnestly. &ldquo;You invite my opinion; I trust you
      will accept it for what it is worth. Before you utter another word against
      Frederic, let me remind you that I have known both of you for a long, long
      time. In all the years I have been in this house I have never known you to
      grant him a tender, loving word. My heart has ached for him. There have
      been times when I almost hated you. He feels your neglect, your harshness,
      your&mdash;your cruelty. He&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Cruelty!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It is nothing less. You do not like him. I cannot understand why you
      should treat him as you do. He shrinks from you. Is it right, Mr Brood,
      that a son should shrink from his father as a dog cringes at the voice of
      an unkind master? I might be able to understand your attitude toward him
      if your unkindness was of recent origin, but&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Recent origin?&rdquo; he demanded quickly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;If it had begun with the advent of Mrs Brood,&rdquo; she explained frankly,
      undismayed by his scowl. &ldquo;I do not understand all that has gone before. Is
      it surprising, Mr Brood, that your son finds it difficult to love you? Do
      you deserve&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Brood stopped her with a gesture of his hand.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The time has come for frankness on my part. You set me an example, Lydia.
      You have the courage of your father. For months I have had it in my mind
      to tell you the truth about Frederic, but my courage has always failed me.
      Perhaps I use the wrong word. It may be something very unlike cowardice
      that has held me back. I am going to put a direct question to you first of
      all, and I ask you to answer truthfully. Would you say that Frederic is
      like&mdash;that is, resembles his father?&rdquo; He was leaning forward, his
      manner intense.
    </p>
    <p>
      Lydia was surprised.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What an odd thing to say! Of course he resembles his father. I have never
      seen a portrait of his mother, but&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You mean that he looks like me?&rdquo; demanded Brood.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Certainly. What do you mean?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Brood laughed, a short, ugly laugh&mdash;and then fingered his chin
      nervously.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He resembles his mother,&rdquo; he said.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;When he is angry he is very much like you, Mr Brood. I have often
      wondered why he is unlike you at other times. Now I know. He is like his
      mother. She must have been lovely, gentle, patient&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Wait! Suppose I were to tell you that Frederic is not my son?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I should not believe you, Mr Brood,&rdquo; she replied flatly. &ldquo;What is it that
      you are trying to say to me?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He turned away abruptly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I will not go on with it. The subject is closed. There is nothing to tell&mdash;at
      present.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She placed herself in front of him, resolute and determined.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I insist, Mr Brood. The time <i>has</i> come for you to be frank. You
      must tell me what you meant by that remark.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Has your mother never told you anything concerning my past life?&rdquo; he
      demanded.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What has my mother to do with your past life?&rdquo; she inquired, suddenly
      afraid.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I refer only to what she may have heard from your father. He knew more
      than any of them. I confided in him to a great extent. I had to unburden
      myself to someone. He was my best friend. It is not improbable that he
      repeated certain parts of my story to your mother.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;She has told me that you&mdash;you were not happy, Mr Brood.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Is that all?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&mdash;I think so.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Is that all?&rdquo; he insisted.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;When I was a little girl I heard my father say to her that your life had
      been ruined by&mdash;well, that your marriage had turned out badly,&rdquo; she
      confessed haltingly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What more did he say?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He said&mdash;I remember feeling terribly about it&mdash;he said you had
      driven your wife out of this very house.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Did he speak of another man?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes. Her music-master.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You were too young to know what that meant, eh?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I knew that you never saw her after&mdash;after she left this house.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Will you understand how horrible it all was if I say to you now that&mdash;Frederic
      is not my son?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Her eyes filled with horror.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;How can you say such a thing, Mr Brood? He is your son. How can you say&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;His father is the man who wrote the accursed waltz he has just been
      playing! Could there be anything more devilish than the conviction it
      carries? After all these years, he&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Stop, Mr Brood!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am sorry if I hurt you, Lydia. You have asked me why I hate him. Need I
      say anything more?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You have only made me love him more than ever before. You cannot hurt me
      through Frederic.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am sorry that it has come to such a pass as this. It is not right that
      you should be made to suffer, too.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I do not believe all that you have told me. He <i>is</i> your son. He <i>is</i>,
      Mr Brood.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I would to God I could believe that!&rdquo; he cried in a voice of agony. &ldquo;I
      would to God it were true!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You could believe it if you chose to believe your own eyes, your own
      heart.&rdquo; She lowered her voice to a half whisper. &ldquo;Does&mdash;does Frederic
      know? Does he know that his mother&mdash;oh, I can't believe it!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He does not know.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And you did drive her out of this house?&rdquo; Brood did not answer. &ldquo;You sent
      her away and and kept her boy, the boy who was nothing to you? Nothing!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I kept him,&rdquo; he said, with a queer smile on his lips.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;All these years? He never knew his mother?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He has never heard her name spoken.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And she?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I only know that she is dead. She never saw him after&mdash;after that
      day.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And now, Mr Brood, may I ask why you have always intended to tell me this
      dreadful thing?&rdquo; she demanded, her eyes gleaming with a fierce, accusing
      light.
    </p>
    <p>
      He stared. &ldquo;Doesn't&mdash;doesn't it put a different light on your
      estimate of him? Doesn't it convince you that he is not worthy of&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No! A thousand times no!&rdquo; she cried. &ldquo;I love him. If he were to ask me to
      be his wife tonight I would rejoice&mdash;oh, I would rejoice! Someone is
      coming. Let me say this to you, Mr Brood: you have brought Frederic up as
      a butcher fattens the calves and swine he prepares for slaughter. You are
      waiting for the hour to come when you can kill his very soul with the
      weapon you have held over him for so long, waiting, waiting, waiting! In
      God's name, what has <i>he</i> done that you should want to strike him
      down after all these years? It is in my heart to curse you, but somehow I
      feel that you are a curse to yourself. I will not say that I cannot
      understand how you feel about everything. You have suffered. I know you
      have, and I&mdash;I am sorry for you. And knowing how bitter life has been
      for you, I implore you to be merciful to him who is innocent.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The man listened without the slightest change of expression. The lines
      seemed deeper about his eyes, that was all. But the eyes were bright and
      as hard as the steel they resembled.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You would marry him?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, yes!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Knowing that he is a scoundrel?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;How dare you say that, Mr Brood?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Because,&rdquo; said he levelly, &ldquo;he <i>thinks</i> he is my son.&rdquo; Voices were
      heard on the stairs, Frederic's and Yvonne's. &ldquo;He is coming now, my dear,&rdquo;
       he went on, and then, after a pause fraught with significance, &ldquo;and my
      wife is with him.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Lydia closed her eyes, as if in dire pain. A dry sob was in her throat.
    </p>
    <p>
      A strange thing happened to Brood, the man of iron. Tears suddenly rushed
      to his eyes.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <a name="link2HCH0012" id="link2HCH0012"> </a>
    </p>
    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER XII
    </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">Y</span>vonne stopped in
      the doorway. Ranjab was holding the curtains aside for her to enter. The
      tall figure of Frederic loomed up behind her, his dark face glowing in the
      warm light that came from the room. She had changed her dress for an
      exquisite orchid-coloured tea-gown of chiffon under the rarest and most
      delicate of lace. For an instant her gaze rested on Lydia, and then went
      questioningly to Brood's face. The girl's confusion had not escaped her
      notice. Her husband's manner was but little less convicting. Her eyes
      narrowed.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ranjab said you were expecting us,&rdquo; she said slowly, with marked emphasis
      on the participle. She came forward haltingly, as if in doubt as to her
      welcome. &ldquo;Are we interrupting?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Of course not,&rdquo; said Brood, a flush of annoyance on his cheek. &ldquo;Lydia is
      tired. I sent Ranjab down to ask Frederic to&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Frederic interrupted, a trifle too eagerly. &ldquo;I'll walk around with you,
      Lydia. It's raining, however. Shall I get the car out, father?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, no!&rdquo; cried Lydia, painfully conscious of the rather awkward
      situation. &ldquo;And please don't bother, Freddy. I can go home alone. It's
      only a step.&rdquo; She moved toward the door, eager to be away.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I'll go with you,&rdquo; said Frederic decisively. He stood between her and the
      door, an embarrassed smile on his lips. &ldquo;I've got something to say to you,
      Lydia,&rdquo; he went on, lowering his voice.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;James dear,&rdquo; said Mrs Brood, shaking her finger at her husband, and with
      an exasperating smile on her lips, &ldquo;you are working the poor girl too
      hard. See how late it is! And how nervous she is. Why, you are trembling,
      Lydia! For shame, James.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am a little tired,&rdquo; stammered Lydia. &ldquo;We are working so hard, you know,
      in order to finish the&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Brood interrupted, his tone sharp and incisive.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The end is in sight. We're a bit feverish over it, I suppose. You see, my
      dear, we have just escaped captivity in Thassa. It was a bit thrilling, I
      fancy. But we've stopped for the night.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;So I perceive,&rdquo; said Yvonne, a touch of insolence in her voice. &ldquo;You
      stopped, I dare say, when you heard the tread of the vulgar world
      approaching the inner temple. That is what you broke into and desecrated,
      wasn't it?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The inner temple at Thassa,&rdquo; he said coldly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Certainly. The place you were escaping from when we came in.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      It was clear to all of them that Yvonne was piqued, even angry. She
      deliberately crossed the room and threw herself upon the couch, an act so
      childish, so disdainful, that for a full minute no one spoke, but stared
      at her, each with a different emotion.
    </p>
    <p>
      Lydia's eyes were flashing. Her lips parted, but she withheld the angry
      words that rose to them.
    </p>
    <p>
      Brood's expression changed slowly from dull anger to one of incredulity,
      which swiftly gave way to positive joy. His wife was jealous!
    </p>
    <p>
      Frederic was biting his lips nervously. He allowed Lydia to pass him on
      her way out, scarcely noticing her, so intently was his gaze fixed upon
      Yvonne. When Brood followed Lydia into the hall to remonstrate, the young
      man sprang eagerly to his stepmother's side.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Good Lord, Yvonne!&rdquo; he whispered, &ldquo;that was a nasty thing to say. What
      will Lydia think? By gad, is it possible that you are jealous? Of Lydia?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Jealous?&rdquo; cried she, struggling with her fury. &ldquo;Jealous of that girl?
      Poof! Why should I be jealous of her? She hasn't the blood of a potato!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I can't understand you,&rdquo; he said in great perplexity. &ldquo;You&mdash;you told
      me to-night that you are not sure that you really love him. You&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She stopped him with a quick gesture. Her eyes were smouldering. &ldquo;Where is
      he? Gone away with her? Go and look; do.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;They're in the hall. I shall take her home, never fear. I fancy he's
      trying to explain your insinuating&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She turned on him furiously. &ldquo;Are you lecturing me? What a tempest in a
      teapot!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Lydia's as good as gold. She&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Then take her home at once,&rdquo; sneered Yvonne. &ldquo;This is no place for her.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Frederic paled. &ldquo;You're not trying to say my father would&mdash;good Lord,
      Yvonne, you must be crazy! Why, that is impossible! If&mdash;if I thought&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
       He clenched his fists and glared over his shoulder, missing the queer
      little smile that flitted across her face.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You do love her then,&rdquo; she said, her voice suddenly soft and caressing.
    </p>
    <p>
      He stared at her in complete bewilderment.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&mdash;I&mdash;Lord, you gave me a shock!&rdquo; He passed his hand across his
      moist forehead. &ldquo;It can't be so. Why, the very thought of it&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I suppose I shall have to apologise to Lydia,&rdquo; said she calmly. &ldquo;Your
      father will exact it of me, and I shall obey. How does it sound, coming
      from me? 'I am sorry, Lydia.' Do I say it prettily?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I don't understand you at all, Yvonne. I adore you, and yet, by Heaven, I&mdash;I
      actually believe I hated you just now. Listen to me. I've been treating
      Lydia vilely for a long, long time, but&mdash;she's the finest, best,
      dearest girl in the world. You&mdash;even you, Yvonne&mdash;shall not
      utter a word against&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;<i>Ae!</i> What heroics!&rdquo; she cried ironically.
      &ldquo;You are splendid when you are angry, my son. Yes, you are almost as
      splendid as your father. He, too, has been angry with me. He, too, has
      made me shudder. But he, too, has forgiven me, as you shall this instant.
      Say it, Freddy. You do forgive me? I was mean, nasty, ugly, vile&mdash;oh,
      everything that's horrid. I take it all back. Now be nice to me!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She laid her hand on his arm, an appealing little caress that conquered
      him in a flash. He clasped her fingers fiercely in his and mumbled
      incoherently as he leaned forward, drawn resistlessly nearer by the
      strange magic that was hers.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You&mdash;you are wonderful,&rdquo; he murmured. &ldquo;I knew you'd regret what you
      said. You couldn't have meant it.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She smiled, patted his hand gently, and allowed her swimming eyes to rest
      on his for an instant to complete the conquest. Then she motioned him
      away. Brood's voice was heard in the doorway. She had, however, planted an
      insidious thing in Frederic's mind, and it would grow.
    </p>
    <p>
      Her husband re-entered the room, his arm linked in Lydia's. Frederic was
      at the table lighting a cigarette.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You did not mean all that you said a moment ago, Yvonne,&rdquo; said Brood
      levelly. &ldquo;Lydia misinterpreted your jest. You meant nothing unkind, I am
      sure.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He was looking straight into her rebellious eyes. The last gleam of
      defiance died out of them as he spoke.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am sorry, Lydia darling,&rdquo; she said, and reached out her hand to the
      girl who approached reluctantly, uncertainly. &ldquo;I confess that I was
      jealous. Why shouldn't I be jealous? You are so beautiful, so splendid.&rdquo;
       She drew the girl down beside her. &ldquo;Forgive me, dear.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Lydia, whose honest heart had been so full of resentment the moment
      before, could not withstand the humble appeal in the voice of the
      penitent.
    </p>
    <p>
      She smiled, first at Yvonne, then at Brood, and never quite understood the
      impulse that ordered her to kiss the warm, red lips that so recently had
      offended.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;James dear,&rdquo; fell softly, alluringly, from Yvonne's now tremulous lips.
      He sprang to her side. She kissed him passionately. &ldquo;Now we are all
      ourselves once more,&rdquo; she gasped a moment later, her eyes still fixed
      inquiringly on those of the man beside her. &ldquo;Let us be gay! Let us forget!
      Come, Frederic! Sit here at my feet. Lydia is not going home yet. Ranjab,
      the cigarettes!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Frederic, white-faced and scowling, remained at the window, glaring out
      into the rain-swept night. A steady sheet of raindrops thrashed against
      the window-panes.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Hear the wind!&rdquo; cried Yvonne, after a single sharp glance at his tall,
      motionless figure. &ldquo;One can almost imagine that ghosts from every
      graveyard in the world are whistling past our windows. Should we not
      rejoice? We have them safely locked outside. There are no ghosts in
      here to make us shiver&mdash;and&mdash;shake.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The sentence that began so glibly trailed off in a slow crescendo, ending
      abruptly. Ranjab was holding the lighted taper for her cigarette. As she
      spoke her eyes were lifted to his dark, saturnine face. She was saying
      there were no ghosts when his eyes suddenly fastened on hers. In spite of
      herself her voice rose in response to the curious dread that chilled her
      heart as she looked into the shining mirrors above her. She shivered as if
      in the presence of death! For an incalculably brief period their gaze
      remained fixed and steady, each reading a mystery. Then the Hindu lowered
      his heavy lashes and moved away. The little by-scene did not go unnoticed
      by the others, although its meaning was lost.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;There's nothing to be afraid of, Yvonne,&rdquo; said Brood, pressing the hand
      which trembled in his.
      &ldquo;Your imagination carries you a long way. Are you really afraid of
      ghosts?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She answered in a deep, solemn voice that carried conviction.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I believe in ghosts. I believe the dead come back to us, not to flit
      about as we are told by superstition, but to lodge&mdash;actually to dwell&mdash;inside
      these warm, living bodies of ours. They come and go at will. Sometimes we
      feel that they are there, but&mdash;oh, who knows? Their souls may conquer ours
      and go on inhabiting&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nonsense!&rdquo; cried her husband. &ldquo;Once dead, always dead, my dear.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Do you really believe that, James?&rdquo; she demanded seriously. &ldquo;Have you
      never felt that something that was not you was living, breathing, speaking
      in this earthly shell of yours? Something that was not you, I say.
      Something that&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Never!&rdquo; he exclaimed quickly, but his eyes were full of the wonder that
      he felt.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Frederic,&rdquo; she called imperatively, &ldquo;come away from that window!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The young man joined the group. The sullen look in his face had given way
      to one of acute inquiry. The new note in her voice produced a strange
      effect upon him. It seemed like a call for help, a cry out of the
      darkness.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It is raining pitchforks,&rdquo; he said, as if to explain his failure to
      respond at the first call.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, dear,&rdquo; sighed Lydia uncomfortably.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You can't go out in the storm, my dear,&rdquo; cried Yvonne, tightening her
      grip on the girl's arm. &ldquo;Draw up a chair, Freddy. Let's be cosy.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Really, Mrs Brood, I should go at once. Mother&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Your mother is in bed and asleep,&rdquo; protested Yvonne.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We should all be in bed,&rdquo; said Frederic.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;A bed is a sepulchre. We bury half our lives in it, Frederic. We spend
      too much time in bed. Why live in our dreams when we should be enjoying
      to-day and not our yesterdays? Do you want to hear about the concert,
      James? It was wonderful. The&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;If it was so wonderful, why did you leave before it was over?&rdquo; demanded
      her husband, his lips straightening.
    </p>
    <p>
      She looked at him curiously.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;How do you know that we left before it was over?&rdquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You have been at home since ten.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      They were all playing for time. They all realised that something sinister
      was attending their little conclave, unseen but vital. Each one knew that
      united they were safe, each against the other! Lydia was afraid because
      of Brood's revelations. Yvonne had sensed peril with the message delivered
      by Ranjab to Frederic. Frederic had come upstairs prepared for rebellion
      against the caustic remarks that were almost certain to come from his
      father. Brood was afraid of&mdash;himself! He was holding himself in check
      with the greatest difficulty. He knew that the smallest spark would create
      the explosion he dreaded and yet courted. Restraint lay heavily, yet
      shiftingly, upon all of them.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh,&rdquo; said Yvonne easily, &ldquo;there were still two numbers to be played, and
      I loathe both of them. Frederic was ready to come away, too.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And Dr Hodder? Did he come away with you?&rdquo; inquired Brood.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No. He insisted on staying to the bitter end. We left him there.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Brood laughed shortly. &ldquo;I see.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He said he would come down with the Gunnings,&rdquo; explained Yvonne, her eyes
      flickering. &ldquo;Besides, I always feel as though I were riding in an
      ambulance when he is in the car. He dissected every bit of music they
      played to-night. Now, James dear, you know he is quite dreadful.&rdquo; She said
      it pleadingly, poutingly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I offered to send the car back for him,&rdquo; said Frederic, speaking for the
      first time.
    </p>
    <p>
      Brood drew a long breath. His glance met Lydia's and recognised the mute
      appeal that lay in her eyes. He smiled faintly, and hope rose in her
      troubled breast.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The Gunnings were there,&rdquo; put in Yvonne, puffing more rapidly than usual
      at her cigarette. &ldquo;They came to the box with Mr and Mrs Harbison during
      the intermission.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What spiteful things did Mrs Harbison say about me?&rdquo; demanded Brood,
      affecting a certain lightness of manner. &ldquo;A cigarette, Ranjab. She
      despises me, I'm sure. Didn't she ask why I was not there to look after my
      beautiful and much-coveted wife?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;She said that you interested her more than any man she knew, and, of
      course, I considered that particularly spiteful. Her husband declared he
      would rather shoot with you than with any man in the world. He's very
      tiresome.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We've hunted a good bit together,&rdquo; said Brood.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Harbison says you are the most deadly shot he's ever seen,&rdquo; said
      Frederic, relaxing slightly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What was it he said about your wonderful accuracy with a revolver? What
      was it, Frederic? Hitting a shilling at some dreadful distance&mdash;thirty
      yards, eh?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Thirty paces,&rdquo; said Frederic.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;My father often spoke of your shooting with a revolver, Mr Brood,&rdquo; said
      Lydia. &ldquo;He said it was really marvellous.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Yvonne laughed. &ldquo;How interesting to have a husband who can even see as far
      as thirty paces. But revolver shooting is a doubtful accomplishment in
      these days of peace, isn't it? What is there to shoot at?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Mad dogs and&mdash;men,&rdquo; said Brood. Lydia's look required an answer.
      &ldquo;No, I've never shot a mad dog, Lydia.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Who was the young woman with the lisp, Freddy?&rdquo; asked Yvonne abruptly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Miss Dangerfield. Isn't she amusing? I love that soft Virginia drawl of
      hers. She's pretty, too. Old Hodder was quite taken with her.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      A long, reverberating roll of thunder, ending in an ear-splitting crash
      that seemed no farther away than the window casement behind them, brought
      sharp exclamations of terror from the lips of the two women. The men,
      appalled, started to their feet.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Good Lord, that <i>was</i> close!&rdquo; cried Frederic. &ldquo;There was no sign of
      a storm when we came in&mdash;just a steady, gentle spring rain.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am frightened,&rdquo; shuddered Yvonne, wide-eyed with fear. &ldquo;Do you think&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It struck near by, that's all,&rdquo; said Brood. &ldquo;Lightning bolts are
      deceptive. One may think they strike at one's very elbow, and yet the spot
      is really miles away. I hope your mother is not distressed, my dear,&rdquo;
       turning to Lydia. &ldquo;She is afraid of the lightning, I know.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Lydia sprang to her feet. &ldquo;I must go home at once, Mr Brood. She will be
      dreadfully frightened. I&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      There came another deafening crash. The glare filled the room with a
      brilliant, greenish hue. Ranjab was standing at the window, holding the
      curtains apart while he peered upward across the space that separated them
      from the apartment building beyond the court.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Take me home, Frederic!&rdquo; cried Lydia frantically. She ran toward the
      door.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Let me telephone to your mother, Lyddy,&rdquo; he cried, hurrying after her
      into the hall.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No! no! no!&rdquo; she gasped as she ran. &ldquo;Don't come with me if you&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I will come!&rdquo; he exclaimed, as they raced down the stairs. &ldquo;Don't be
      frightened, darling. It's all right. Listen to me! Mrs Desmond is as safe
      as&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, Freddy, Freddy!&rdquo; she wailed, breaking under a strain that he was not
      by way of comprehending. &ldquo;Oh, Freddy dear!&rdquo; Her nerves gave way. She was
      sobbing convulsively when they came to the lower hall.
    </p>
    <p>
      In great distress he clasped her in his arms, mumbling incoherent words of
      love, encouragement&mdash;even ridicule for the fear she betrayed. Far
      from his mind was the real cause of her unhappy plight.
    </p>
    <p>
      He held her close to his breast, and there she sobbed and trembled as with
      a mighty, racking chill. Her fingers clutched his arm with the grip of one
      who clings to the edge of a precipice with death below. Her face was
      buried against his shoulder.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;There! There!&rdquo; he murmured, appalled by this wild display of fear. &ldquo;Don't
      worry, darling. Everything is all right. Oh, you dear, dear girlie!
      Please, please! My little Lyddy!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Take me home, Freddy&mdash;take me home,&rdquo; she whispered brokenly. &ldquo;I
      cannot stay here another second. Come, dearest&mdash;come home with me.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Still they stood there in the dark hall, clasped in each other's arms&mdash;stood
      there for many minutes without realising the lapse of time, thinking not
      of Mrs Desmond nor the storm that raged outside, but of the storm they
      were weathering together with the lightning racing through their veins,
      thunder in their heart-beats.
    </p>
    <p>
      A footstep in the hall. Frederic looked up, dazed, bewildered. Jones, the
      butler, was retreating through a door near by, having come upon them
      unexpectedly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&mdash;I beg pardon, sir. I&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, Jones! Listen! My raincoat&mdash;and father's, quick. And Miss
      Lydia's things. Yes, yes, it's all right, Jones. It's quite all right.&rdquo;
       Frederic was calling out the sentences jerkily.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Quite all right,&rdquo; repeated Jones, his throat swelling, his eyes suddenly
      dim. &ldquo;Quite, sir. Yes, yes!&rdquo; He rushed into the closet at the end of the
      hall, more grievously upset than he ever had been in all his life before.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You will come with me, Freddy?&rdquo; she was whispering, clinging to him as
      one in panic.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, yes. Don't be frightened, Lyddy. I&mdash;I know everything is all
      right now. I'm sure of it.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, I am sure, too, dear. I have always been sure,&rdquo; she cried, and he
      understood, as she had understood.
    </p>
    <p>
      Despite the protests of Jones they dashed out into the blighting
      thunderstorm. The rain beat down in torrents, the din was infernal. As the
      door closed behind them Lydia, in the ecstasy of freedom from restraint
      bitterly imposed, gave vent to a shrill cry of relief. Words, the meaning
      of which he could not grasp, babbled from her lips as they descended the
      steps. One sentence fell vaguely clear from the others, and it puzzled
      him. He was sure that she said:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, I am so glad, so happy we are out of that house&mdash;you and I
      together.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Close together, holding tightly to each other, they breasted the swirling
      sheets of rain. The big umbrella was of little protection to them,
      although held manfully to break the force of the cold flood of waters.
      They bent their strong young bodies against the wind, and a sort of wild,
      impish hilarity took possession of them. It was freedom, after all! They
      were fighting a force in nature that they understood, and the sharp,
      staccato cries that came from their lips were born of an exultant glee
      which neither of them could have suppressed or controlled. Their hearts
      were as wild as the tempest about them.
    </p>
    <p>
      They turned the corner and were flanked by the wind and rain. The long
      raincoats flattened their sleek, dripping folds tightly against their
      bodies. It was almost impossible to push forward into this mad deluge. The
      umbrella, caught by a gust, was turned inside out, and the full force of
      the storm struck upon their faces, almost taking the breath away. And they
      laughed as their arms tightened about each other. As one person they
      breasted the gale.
    </p>
    <p>
      They were fairly blown through the doors of the apartment-house. Mrs
      Desmond threw open the door as their wet, soggy feet came sloshing down
      the hall. Frederic's arm was about Lydia as they approached, and both of
      their drenched faces were wreathed in smiles&mdash;gay, exalted smiles.
      The mother, white-faced and fearful, stared for a second at the amazing
      pair, and then held out her arms to them.
    </p>
    <p>
      She was drenched in their embrace, but no one thought of the havoc that
      was being created in that swift, impulsive contact.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It's a fine mess we've made of your rug, Mrs Desmond,&rdquo; said Frederic
      ruefully a few minutes later.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Goodness!&rdquo; cried Lydia, aghast. Then they all realised.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Take those horrid things off at once, both of you,&rdquo; commanded Mrs
      Desmond. Her voice trembled. &ldquo;And your shoes&mdash;and stockings. Dear,
      dear!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I must run back home!&rdquo; exclaimed Frederic.
    </p>
    <p>
      Lydia placed herself between him and the door.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No! I want you to stay!&rdquo; she cried.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Stay?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You shall not go out in that dreadful storm again. I will not let you go,
      Frederic. Stay&mdash;stay here with me.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He stared. &ldquo;What a funny idea!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Wait until the rain is over,&rdquo; added Mrs Desmond.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, no!&rdquo; cried Lydia. &ldquo;I mean for him to stay here the rest of the night.
      We can put you up, Freddy. I&mdash;I don't want you to go back there until&mdash;until
      to-morrow.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      A glad light broke in his face. &ldquo;By Jove, I&mdash;do you know, I'd like to
      stay? I&mdash;I really would, Mrs Desmond. Can you find a place for me?&rdquo;
       His voice was eager, his eyes sparkling.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes,&rdquo; said the mother quietly, almost serenely. &ldquo;You shall have Lydia's
      bed, Frederic. She can come in with me. Yes, you must stay. Are you not
      our Frederic?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Thank you,&rdquo; he stammered, and his eyes fell.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I will telephone to Jones when the storm abates,&rdquo; said Mrs Desmond. &ldquo;Now
      get out of those coats, and&mdash;oh, dear, how wet you are! A hot drink
      for both.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Would you mind asking Jones to send over something for me to wear in the
      morning?&rdquo; said Frederic, grinning as he stood forth in his evening
      clothes.
    </p>
    <p>
      Ten minutes later, in a dressing-gown and bare feet, he sat with them
      before an open fire and sipped the toddy she had brewed.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I say, this is great!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Lydia was suddenly shy and embarrassed.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Good night,&rdquo; she whispered. Her fingers brushed his cheek lightly.
    </p>
    <p>
      He drew her down to him and kissed her passionately.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Good night, my Lyddy!&rdquo; he said softly, his cheek flushing.
    </p>
    <p>
      She went quickly from the room.
    </p>
    <p>
      Later he stood in her sweet, dainty little bedroom and looked about him
      with a feeling of mingled awe and wonder. All of her intimate, exquisite
      belongings, the sanctified treasures of her most secret domain, were all
      about him.
    </p>
    <p>
      He fingered the articles on her dressing-table; smelled of the perfume
      bottles and smiled as he recognised the sweet odours as being a part of
      her, and not a thing unto themselves; grinned delightedly at his own
      photograph in its silver frame that stood where she could see it the last
      thing at night and the first in the morning; caressed&mdash;aye, caressed&mdash;the
      little hand-mirror that had reflected her gay or troubled face so many
      times since the dear Christmas Day when he had given it to her with his
      love.
    </p>
    <p>
      He stood beside her bed where she had stood, and the soft rug seemed to
      respond to the delightful tingling that ran through his bare feet. Her
      room! Her bed! Her domain!
    </p>
    <p>
      Suddenly he dropped to his knees and buried his hot face in the cool white
      sheets and kissed them over and over again. Here was sanctuary! His eyes
      were wet with tears when he arose to his feet, and his arms went out to
      the closed door.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;My Lyddy!&rdquo; he whispered chokingly.
    </p>
    <p>
      Back there in the rose-hued light of James Brood's study Yvonne cringed
      and shook in the strong arms of her husband all through that savage storm.
      She was no longer the defiant, self-possessed creature he had come to know
      so well, but a shrinking, trembling child, stripped of all her bravado,
      all her arrogance, all her seeming guile. A pathetic whimper crooned from
      her lips in response to his gentle words of reassurance. She was afraid&mdash;desperately
      afraid&mdash;and she crept close to him in her fear.
    </p>
    <p>
      And he? He was looking backward to another who had nestled close to him
      and whimpered as she was doing now&mdash;another who lived in terror when
      it stormed.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <a name="link2HCH0013" id="link2HCH0013"> </a>
    </p>
    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER XIII
    </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">F</span>rederic opened his
      eyes at the sound of a gentle, persistent tapping on the bedroom door.
      Resting on his elbow, he looked blankly, wonderingly, about the room, and&mdash;remembered.
      The sun streamed into the chamber, filling it with a radiance that almost
      dazzled him. He rubbed his eyes, and again, as in the night just gone, his
      thought absorbed the contents of the room.
    </p>
    <p>
      He had not dreamed it, after all. He was there in Lydia's bed, attended by
      all the mute, inanimate sentinels that stood guard over her while she
      slept. The knocking continued. He dreamed on, his blinking eyes still
      seeking out the dainty, Lydia-like treasures in the enchanted room.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Frederic!&rdquo; called a voice outside the door.
    </p>
    <p>
      He started guiltily.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;All right,&rdquo; was his cheery response.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Get up! It's nine o'clock. Or will you have your breakfast in bed, sir?&rdquo;
       It was Lydia who spoke, assuming a fine Irish brogue in imitation of their
      little maid of all work.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I'll have to, unless my clothes have come over!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;They are here. Now do hurry.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He sprang out of bed and bounded across the room. She passed the garments
      through the partly opened door.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Morning!&rdquo; he greeted, sticking his tousled head around the edge.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Morning!&rdquo; she responded as briefly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Don't wait breakfast for me. I'll skip over home&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It will be ready in fifteen minutes,&rdquo; she said arbitrarily. &ldquo;Don't
      dawdle.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;How pretty, how sweet you are this morning,&rdquo; he cried, his dark eyes
      dancing.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Silly!&rdquo; she scoffed, but with a radiant smile. Then, with a perfectly
      childish giggle, she slammed the door and scurried away as if in fear of
      pursuit.
    </p>
    <p>
      He was artistic, temperamental. Such as he have not the capacity for haste
      when there is the slightest opportunity to dream and dawdle. He was a full
      quarter of an hour taking his tub, and another was consumed in getting
      into his clothes. At home he was always much longer than this, for he was
      delayed by the additional task of selecting shirts, ties, socks, and
      scarf-pins, and changing his mind and all of them three or four times
      before being satisfied with the effect. He sallied forth in great haste at
      nine thirty-five, and was extremely proud of himself, although unshaved.
    </p>
    <p>
      His first act, after warmly greeting Mrs Desmond, was to sit down at the
      piano. Hurriedly he played a few jerky, broken snatches of the haunting
      air he had heard the night before.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I've been wondering if I could remember it,&rdquo; he apologised, as he
      followed them into the dining-room. &ldquo;What's the matter, Lyddy? Didn't you
      sleep well? Poor old girl, I was a beast to deprive you of your bed.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I have a mean headache, that's all,&rdquo; said the girl quickly. He noticed
      the dark circles under her eyes and the queer expression, as of trouble,
      in their depths. &ldquo;It will go as soon as I've had my coffee.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Night, with its wonderful sensations, was behind them. Day revealed the
      shadow that had fallen. They unconsciously shrank from it and drew back
      into the shelter of their own misgivings. The joyous abandon of the night
      before was dead. Over its grave stood the leering spectre of unrest.
    </p>
    <p>
      When he took her in his arms later on, and kissed her, there was not the
      shadow of a doubt in the mind of either that the restraining influence of
      a condition over which they had no control was there to mock their
      endeavour to be natural. They were not to be deceived by the apparent
      earnestness of the embrace. Each knew that the other was asking a
      question, even as their lips met and clung in the rather pathetic attempt
      to confirm the fond dream of the night before. They kissed as through a
      veil. They were awake once more, and they were wary, unconvinced. The
      answer to their questions came in the kiss itself, and constraint fell
      upon them.
    </p>
    <p>
      Drawn by an impulse that had been struggling within him, Frederic found
      himself standing at the sitting-room window. It was a sly, covert, though
      intensely eager look that he directed at another window far below. If he
      hoped for some sign of life in his father's study he was to be
      disappointed. The curtains hung straight and motionless. He would have
      denied the charge that he longed to see Yvonne sitting in the casement,
      waiting to waft a sign of greeting up to him; he would have denied that
      the thought was in his mind when he went to the window; and yet he was
      conscious of a feeling of disappointment, even annoyance.
    </p>
    <p>
      With considerable adroitness Lydia engaged his attention at the piano.
      Keyed up as she was, his every emotion was plain to her perceptions. She
      had anticipated the motive that led him to the window. She knew that it
      would assert itself in spite of all that he could do to prevent. She
      waited humbly for the thing to happen, pain in her heart, and when her
      reading proved true she was prepared to combat its effect. Music was her
      only ally.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;How does it go, Freddy&mdash;the thing you were playing before
      breakfast?&rdquo; She was trying to pick up the elusive air. &ldquo;It is such a
      fascinating, adorable thing. Is this right?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He looked at his watch. The few bars she had mastered in her eagerness
      fell upon inattentive ears at first. But she persisted. He came over and
      stood beside her. His long, slim fingers joined hers on the keyboard, and
      the sensuous strains of the waltz responded to his touch. He smiled
      patiently as she struggled to repeat what he had played. The fever of the
      thing took hold of him at last, as she had known it would. Leaning over
      her shoulder, his cheek quite close to hers, he played. Her hands dropped
      into her lap.
    </p>
    <p>
      She retained her seat on the bench. Her cunning brain told her that it
      would be a mistake to relinquish her place at the keyboard. He would play
      it through a time or two, mechanically perhaps, and then his interest
      would be gone. He would have gratified her simple request, and that would
      have been the end. She led him on by interrupting time and again in her
      eagerness to grasp the lesson he was giving. Finally she moved over on the
      bench, and he sat down beside her. He was absorbed in the undertaking. His
      brow cleared. His smile was a happy, eager one.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It's a tricky thing, Lyddy,&rdquo; he said enthusiastically, &ldquo;but you'll get
      it. Now listen.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      For an hour they sat there, master and pupil, sweetheart and lover. The
      fear was less in the heart of one when, tiring at last, the other
      contentedly abandoned the rle of taskmaster and threw himself upon the
      couch, remarking, as he stretched himself in luxurious ease:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I like this, Lyddy. I wish you didn't have to go over there and dig away
      at that confounded journal. I like this so well that, 'pon my soul, I'd
      enjoy loafing here with you the whole day long.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Her heart leaped. &ldquo;You shall have your wish, Freddy,&rdquo; she said, barely
      able to conceal the note of eagerness in her voice. &ldquo;I am not going to
      work to-day. I&mdash;my head, you know. Mother telephoned to Mr Brood this
      morning before you were up.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You're going to loaf?&rdquo; he cried gladly. &ldquo;Bully! And I may stay? But, gee,
      I forgot your headache. It will&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo; He was staring up
      from the couch when she hastily broke in, shaking her head vigorously.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Lie still. My head is much better. I want you to stay, dear. I&mdash;I
      want to have you all to myself again. Oh, it will be so good&mdash;so good
      to while away an idle day with you!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She was standing beside the couch. He reached forth and took her hand in
      his, laying it against his lips.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It won't be an idle day,&rdquo; said he seriously. &ldquo;We shall be very busy.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Busy?&rdquo; she inquired apprehensively.
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Talking things over,&rdquo; he said
      briefly. &ldquo;Of course, I ought to go home and face the music.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What do you mean?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It's something I can't talk about, Lyddy. Let's forget our troubles for
      to-day.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Better still, let us share them. Stay here with me. Don't go home to-day,
      Freddy. I&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, I've got to have it out with father some time,&rdquo; he said bitterly. &ldquo;It
      may as well be now as later on. We've got to come to an understanding.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Her heart was cold. She was afraid of what would come out of that
      &ldquo;understanding.&rdquo; All night long she had lain with wide-staring eyes,
      thinking of the horrid thing James Brood had said to her. Far in the night
      she aroused her mother from a sound sleep to put the question that had
      been torturing her for hours. Mrs Desmond confessed that her husband had
      told her that Brood had never considered Frederic to be his son, and then
      the two lay side by side for the remainder of the night without uttering a
      word, and yet keenly awake. They were thinking of the hour when Brood
      would serve notice on the intruder!
    </p>
    <p>
      Lydia now realised that the hour was near. Frederic himself would
      challenge the wrath of all these bitter years, and it would fall upon his
      unsuspecting head with cruel, obliterating force.
    </p>
    <p>
      The girl shivered as with a racking chill. &ldquo;Have it out with father,&rdquo; he
      had said in his ignorance. He was preparing to rush headlong to his doom.
      To prevent that catastrophe was the single, all-absorbing thought in
      Lydia's mind. Her only hope lay in keeping the men apart until she could
      extract from Brood a promise to be merciful, and this she intended to
      accomplish if she had to go down on her knees and grovel before the man.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, Freddy,&rdquo; she cried earnestly, &ldquo;why take the chance of making a bad
      matter worse?&rdquo; Even as she uttered the words she realised how stupid, how
      ineffectual they were.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It can't be much worse,&rdquo; he said gloomily. &ldquo;I am inclined to think he'd
      relish a straight-out, fair, and square talk, anyhow. Moreover, I mean to
      take Yvonne to task for the thing she said&mdash;or implied last night.
      About you, I mean. She&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, I beg of you, don't!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It was&mdash;unspeakable. I don't see what could have come over her.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;She was jealous. She admitted it, dear. If I don't mind, why should you
      incur&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Do you really believe she&mdash;she loves the governor enough to be as
      jealous as all that?&rdquo; he exclaimed, a curious gleam in his eyes&mdash;an
      expression she did not like.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Of course I think so!&rdquo; she cried emphatically. &ldquo;What a question! Have you
      any reason to suspect that she does not love your father?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No&mdash;certainly not,&rdquo; he said in some confusion. Then, after a moment:
      &ldquo;Are you quite sure this headache of yours is real, Lyddy?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What do you mean?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Isn't it an excuse to stay away from&mdash;from Yvonne, after what
      happened last night? Be honest, dear.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She was silent for a long time, weighing her answer. Was it best to be
      honest with him?
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I confess that it has something to do with it,&rdquo; she admitted. Lydia could
      not be anything but truthful.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I thought so. It's&mdash;it's a rotten shame, Lyddy. That's why I want to
      talk to her. I want to reason with her. It's all so perfectly silly, this
      misunderstanding. You've just got to go on as you were before, Lyddy&mdash;just
      as if it hadn't happened. It&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I shall complete the work for your father, Freddy,&rdquo; she said quietly.
      &ldquo;Two or three days more will see the end. After that neither my services
      nor my presence will be required over there.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You don't mean to say&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo; he began, unbelievingly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It isn't likely I'd go there for pleasure, is it?&rdquo; she interrupted dryly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But think of the old times, the&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I can think of them just as well here as anywhere else. No; I shan't
      annoy Mrs Brood, Freddy.&rdquo; It was on the tip of her tongue to say more, but
      she thought better of it.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;They're going abroad soon,&rdquo; he ventured. &ldquo;At least, that's father's plan.
      Yvonne isn't so keen about it. She calls this being abroad, you know.
      Besides,&rdquo; he hurried on in his eagerness to excuse Yvonne, &ldquo;she's
      tremendously fond of you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Lydia was wise. &ldquo;I would give a great deal to be able to really believe
      so, Freddy. I&mdash;I could be very fond of her.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He warmed to the cause.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No end of times she's said you were the finest&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo; Her
      smile&mdash;an odd one, such as he had never seen on her lips before&mdash;checked
      his eager speech. He bridled. &ldquo;Of course, if you don't choose to believe
      me, there's nothing more to be said. She meant it, however.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am sure she said it, Freddy,&rdquo; she hastened to declare. &ldquo;Will she be
      pleased with our&mdash;our marriage?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      It required a great deal of courage on her part to utter these words, but
      she was determined to bring the true situation home to him.
    </p>
    <p>
      He did not even hesitate, and there was conviction in his voice as he
      replied:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It doesn't matter whether she's pleased or displeased. We're pleasing
      ourselves, are we not? There's no one else to consider, dear.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Her eyes were full upon his, and there was wonder in them.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Thank you&mdash;thank you, Freddy,&rdquo; she cried.
      &ldquo;I&mdash;I knew you'd&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo; The sentence remained
      unfinished.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Has there ever been a doubt in your mind?&rdquo; he asked uneasily, after a
      moment. He knew there had been misgivings, and he was ready, in his
      self-abasement, to resent them if given the slightest opening. Guilt made
      him arrogant.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No,&rdquo; she answered simply.
    </p>
    <p>
      The answer was not what he expected. He flushed painfully.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&mdash;I thought perhaps you'd&mdash;you'd get a notion in your head
      that&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo; He, too, stopped for want of the right words to
      express himself without committing the egregious error of letting her see
      that it had been in his thoughts to accuse her of jealousy.
    </p>
    <p>
      She waited for a moment. &ldquo;That I might have got the notion in my head you
      did not love me any longer? Is that what you started to say?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes,&rdquo; he confessed, averting his eyes.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I've been unhappy at times, Freddy, but that is all,&rdquo; she said steadily.
      &ldquo;You see, I know how honest you really are. I know it far better than you
      know it yourself.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I wonder just how honest I am,&rdquo; he muttered.
      &ldquo;I wonder what would happen if&mdash;&mdash;&mdash; But nothing can
      happen. Nothing ever will happen. Thank you, old girl, for saying what you
      said just now. It's&mdash;it's bully of you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He got up and began pacing the floor. She leaned back in her chair,
      deliberately giving him time to straighten out his thoughts for himself.
      Wiser than she knew herself to be, she held back the warm, loving words of
      encouragement, of gratitude, of belief.
    </p>
    <p>
      But she was not prepared for the impetuous appeal that followed. He threw
      himself down beside her and grasped her hands in his. His face seemed
      suddenly old and haggard, his eyes burned like coals of fire. Then, for
      the first time, she had an inkling of the great struggle that had been
      going on inside of him for weeks and weeks.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Listen, Lyddy,&rdquo; he began nervously; &ldquo;will you marry me to-morrow? Are you
      willing to take the chance that I'll be able to support you, to earn
      enough&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Why, Freddy!&rdquo; she cried, half starting up from the couch. She was
      dumbfounded.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Will you? Will you? I mean it,&rdquo; he went on, almost argumentatively.
    </p>
    <p>
      He was very much in earnest, but alas! the fire, the passion of the
      importunate lover was missing. She shrank back into the corner of the
      couch, staring at him with puzzled eyes. Comprehension was slow in
      arriving. As he hurried on with his plea she began to see clearly, her
      sound brain grasped the significance of this sudden decision on his part.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;There's no use waiting, dear. I'll never be more capable of earning a
      living than I am right now. I can go into the office with Brooks any day,
      and I&mdash;I think I can make good. God knows, I can try hard enough. Brooks
      says he's got a place there for me in the bond department. It won't be
      much at first, but I can work into a pretty good&mdash;what's the matter?
      Don't you think I can do it? Have you no faith in me? Are you afraid to
      take a chance?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She had smiled sadly&mdash;it seemed to him reprovingly. His cheek
      flushed.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What has put all this into your head, Freddy dear?&rdquo; she asked shrewdly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Why, good Lord, haven't we had this very thing in mind for years?&rdquo; he
      cried. &ldquo;Haven't we talked about my&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What put it into your head&mdash;just now?&rdquo; she insisted.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I don't know what you're driving at,&rdquo; he floundered.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Don't you think it would be safer&mdash;I mean wiser if you were to wait
      until you are quite certain of yourself, Freddy?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am certain of myself,&rdquo; he exploded. &ldquo;What do you mean? What sort of
      talk is this you are&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Hush! Don't be angry, dear. Be honest now. Don't you understand just what
      I mean?&rdquo; They looked squarely into each other's eyes.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I want you to marry me at once,&rdquo; said he doggedly. &ldquo;You know I love you,
      Lyddy. Is there anything more to say than that?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Don't you want to tell me, Freddy?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      His eyes wavered. &ldquo;I can't go on living as I have been for the past few
      months. I've just got to end it, Lyddy. You don't understand&mdash;you
      can't, and there isn't any use in trying to explain the&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I think I do understand, dear,&rdquo; she said quietly, laying her hand on his.
      &ldquo;I understand so completely that there isn't any use in your trying to
      explain. But don't you think you are a bit cowardly?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Cowardly?&rdquo; he gasped, and then the blood rushed to his face.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Is it quite fair to me&mdash;or to yourself?&rdquo; He was silent. She waited
      for a moment and then went on resolutely. &ldquo;I know just what it is that you
      are afraid of, Freddy. I shall marry you, of course. I love you more than
      anything else in all the world. But are you quite fair in asking me to
      marry you while you are still afraid, dear?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Before God, Lyddy, I love no one else but you!&rdquo; he cried earnestly. &ldquo;I
      know what it is you are thinking, and I&mdash;I don't blame you. But I
      want you <i>now</i>&mdash;you don't know how much I need you now! I want
      to begin a new life with you. I want to feel that you are with me&mdash;just
      you&mdash;strong and brave and enduring. I am adrift. I need you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I know you love me, Frederic. I am absolutely certain of it,&rdquo; she said
      slowly, weighing her words carefully. &ldquo;But I cannot marry you to-morrow&mdash;nor
      for a long time after to-morrow. In a year&mdash;yes. But not now, dear;
      not just now. You&mdash;you understand, don't you? Say that you understand.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      His chin sank upon his breast. &ldquo;Of course I understand,&rdquo; he said in a very
      low voice.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I shall never love you any more than I love you now, Freddy&mdash;never
      so much, perhaps, as at this moment.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I know, Lyddy; I know,&rdquo; he said dully.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;If you insist, I will marry you to-morrow; but you cannot&mdash;you will
      not ask it of me, will you?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But you know I do love you,&rdquo; he cried. &ldquo;There isn't any doubt in your
      mind, Lyddy. There is no one else I tell you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I think I am just beginning to understand men,&rdquo; she remarked
      enigmatically.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And to wonder why they call women the weaker sex, eh?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes,&rdquo; she said, so seriously that the wry smile died on his lips. &ldquo;I
      don't believe there are many women who would ask a man to be sorry for
      them. That's really what all this amounts to, isn't it, Freddy?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;By Jove!&rdquo; he exclaimed wonderingly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You are a strong, self-willed, chivalrous man, and yet you think nothing
      of asking a woman to protect you against yourself; You are afraid to stand
      alone. Wait! You need me because you are a strong man and are afraid that
      your very strength will lead you into ignoble warfare. You are afraid of
      your strength, not of your weakness. So you ask me to help you. Without
      thinking, you ask me to marry you to-morrow. The idea came to you like a
      flash of light in the darkness. Five minutes&mdash;yes, one minute before
      you asked it of me, Freddy dear, you were floundering in the darkness,
      uncertain which way to turn. You were afraid of the things you could not
      see. You looked for some place in which to hide. The flash of light
      revealed a haven of refuge. So you asked me to to marry you to-morrow.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      All through this indictment she had held his hand clasped tightly in both
      of hers. He was looking at her with a frank acknowledgment growing in his
      eyes.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Are you ashamed of me, Lyddy?&rdquo; he asked.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No,&rdquo; she said, meeting his gaze
      steadily. &ldquo;I am a little disappointed, that's all. It is you who are
      ashamed.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am,&rdquo; said he simply. &ldquo;It wasn't fair.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Love will endure. I am content to wait,&rdquo; she said with a wistful smile.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You will be my wife, no matter what happens? You won't let this make any
      difference?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You are not angry with me?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Angry? Why should I be angry with you, Lyddy? For shaking some sense into
      me? For seeing through me with that wonderful, far-sighted brain of yours?
      Why, I could go down on my knees to you. I could&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Let me think, Freddy,&rdquo; she cried, suddenly confronted by her own
      declaration of the night before. She had told James Brood that she would
      marry this discredited son of his the instant he was ready to take her
      unto himself. She had flung that in the older man's face, and she had
      meant every word of it.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&mdash;I take back what I said, dear. I will marry you to-morrow.&rdquo; She
      spoke rapidly, jerkily; her eyes were very dark and luminous.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What has come over you?&rdquo; He stared at her in astonishment. &ldquo;What&mdash;oh,
      I see! You are not sure of me. You&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, yes, I am! It isn't that. I did not know what I was saying when I
      refused to&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, there you go, just like a woman!&rdquo; he cried triumphantly. &ldquo;Spoiling
      everything! You dear, lovable, inconsequent, regular girl! Hurray! Now
      we're back where we began, and I'm holding the whip. You bring me to my
      senses and then promptly lose your own.&rdquo; He clasped her in his arms and
      held her close. &ldquo;You dear, dear Lyddy!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I mean it, dear heart.&rdquo; The whisper smothered in his embrace.
      &ldquo;To-morrow&mdash;to-day, if you will. We will go away. We will&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No,&rdquo; he said, quite resolutely; &ldquo;you have shown me the way. I've just got
      to make good in your estimation before I can hold you to your promise.
      You're splendid, Lyddy; you're wonderful, but&mdash;well, I was unfair a
      while ago. I mean to be fair now. We'll wait. It's better so. I will come
      again and ask you, but it won't be as it was just now. It would not be
      right for me to take you at your word. We'll wait.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Neither spoke for many minutes. It was she who broke the silence.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You must promise one thing, Frederic. For my sake, avoid a quarrel with
      your father. I could not bear that. You will promise, dear? You must.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I don't intend to quarrel with him; but if I am to remain in his house
      there has got to be&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
      He paused, his jaw set stubbornly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Promise me you will wait. He is going away in two weeks. When he returns&mdash;later
      on&mdash;next fall&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, if it really distresses you, Lyddy, I'll&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It does distress me. I want your promise.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I'll do my part,&rdquo; he said resignedly, &ldquo;and next fall will see us married,
      so&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The telephone-bell in the hall was ringing. Frederic released
      Lydia's hand and sat up rather stiffly, as one who suddenly suspects that
      he is being spied upon. The significance of the movement did not escape
      Lydia. She laughed mirthlessly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I will see who it is,&rdquo; she said, and arose. Two red spots appeared in his
      cheeks. Then it was that she realised he had been waiting all along for
      the bell to ring; he had been expecting a summons.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;If it's for me, please say&mdash;er&mdash;say I'll&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
       he began, somewhat disjointedly, but she interrupted him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Will you stay here for luncheon, Frederic? And this afternoon we will go
      to&mdash;oh, is there a concert or a recital&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, I'll stay if you'll let me,&rdquo; he said wistfully. &ldquo;We'll find
      something to do.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She went to the telephone. He heard the polite greetings, the polite
      assurances that she had not taken cold, two or three laughing rejoinders
      to what must have been amusing comments on the storm and its effect on
      timid creatures, and then:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, Mrs Brood, I will call him to the phone.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <a name="link2HCH0014" id="link2HCH0014"> </a>
    </p>
    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER XIV
    </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">F</span>rederic had the
      feeling that he slunk to the telephone. The girl handed the receiver to
      him and he met her confident, untroubled gaze for a second. Instead of
      returning to the sitting-room where she could have heard everything that
      he said, she went into her own room down the hall and closed the door. He
      was not conscious of any intention to temporise, but it was significant
      that he did not speak until the door closed behind her. Afterward he
      realised and was ashamed.
    </p>
    <p>
      Almost the first words that Yvonne uttered were of a nature to puzzle and
      irritate him, although they bore directly upon his own previously formed
      resolution. Her voice, husky and low, seemed strangely plaintive and
      lifeless to him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Have you and Lydia made any plans for the afternoon?&rdquo; she inquired. He
      made haste to declare their intention to attend a concert. &ldquo;I am glad you
      are going to do that,&rdquo; she went on.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Are you ill, Yvonne?&rdquo; he queried suddenly. &ldquo;I? Oh, no. I think I never
      felt better in my life than I do at this moment. The storm must have blown
      the cobwebs out of my brain. I believe I'm quite happy to-day, Frederic.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Aren't you always happy?&rdquo; he cried chidingly. &ldquo;What an odd thing to say.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She did not respond to this.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You will stay for luncheon with Lydia?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes. She's trying to pick up that thing of Feverelli's&mdash;the one we
      heard last night.&rdquo; There was silence at the other end of the wire, &ldquo;Are
      you there?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I'm teaching it to her.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I see.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I will be home for dinner, of course. You&mdash;you don't need me for
      anything, do you?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No,&rdquo; she said. Then, with a low laugh: &ldquo;You may be excused for the day,
      my son.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What's wrong?&rdquo; he demanded, lowering his voice.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Wrong? Nothing is wrong. Everything seems right to me. Your father and I
      have been discussing the trip abroad.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Is&mdash;is it settled?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes. We are to sail on the twenty-fifth&mdash;in ten days.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Settled, eh?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I thought you&mdash;you were opposed to going.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I've changed my mind. As a matter of fact, I've changed my heart.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You speak in riddles.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Your father has gone out to arrange for passage on the <i>Olympic</i>. He
      is lunching at the Lawyers' Club.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You will lunch alone, then?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Naturally.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He suppressed an impulse.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I'm sorry, Yvonne.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She was silent for a long time.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Frederic, I want you to do something for me.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&mdash;I've promised Lydia to stay here&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, it isn't that. Will you try to convince Lydia that I meant no offence
      last night when I&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;She understands all that perfectly, Yvonne.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, she doesn't. A woman <i>wouldn't</i> understand.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I will square everything,&rdquo; he said.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It means a great deal to me,&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;In what way?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      There was a pause.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No woman likes to be regarded as a fool,&rdquo; she said at last, apparently
      after careful reflection.
      &ldquo;Oh, yes; there is something else. We are dining out this evening.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You and I?&rdquo; he asked, after a moment.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Certainly not. Your father and I. I was about to suggest that you dine
      with Lydia&mdash;or, better still, ask her over here to share your dinner
      with you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He was scowling.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Where are you going?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Going? Oh, dining. I see. Well,&rdquo; slowly, deliberately, &ldquo;we thought it
      would be great fun to dine alone at Delmonico's and see a play afterward.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Just&mdash;you and father?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We two&mdash;no more.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;How cunning,&rdquo; he sneered.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Will you ask Lydia to dine with you?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Perhaps you will go out somewhere?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I'll have dinner with Mr Dawes and&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That would be jolly. They will be pleased. A sort of&mdash;what do you
      call it&mdash;a sort of reunion, eh?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Are you making sport of me?&rdquo; he demanded angrily.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But no! It will be making sport for the old gentleman, though, <i>ae?</i>
      And now <i>au revoir!</i> You will surely convince Lydia that I love her?
      I am troubled. You will&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What play are you going to see?&rdquo; he cut in. She mentioned a Belasco
      production. &ldquo;Well, I hope you enjoy it, Yvonne. By the way, how is the
      governor to-day? In a good humour?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      There was no response. He waited for a moment and then called out: &ldquo;Are
      you there?&rdquo;.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Good-bye,&rdquo; came back over the wire.
    </p>
    <p>
      He started, as if she had given him a slap in the face. Her voice was cold
      and forbidding.
    </p>
    <p>
      When Lydia rejoined him in the sitting-room he was standing at the window,
      staring across the courtyard far below.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Are you going?&rdquo; she asked steadily.
    </p>
    <p>
      He turned toward her, conscious of the tell-tale scowl that was passing
      from his brow. It did not occur to him to resent her abrupt,
      uncompromising question. As a matter of fact, it seemed quite natural that
      she should put the question in just that way, flatly, incisively. He
      considered himself, in a way, to be on trial.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, I'm not,&rdquo; he replied. &ldquo;You did not expect me to forget, did you?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He was uncomfortable under her honest, inquiring gaze. A sullen anger
      against himself took possession of him. He despised himself for the
      feeling of loneliness and homesickness that suddenly came over him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I thought&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo; she began, and then her brow cleared. &ldquo;I
      have been looking up the recitals in the morning paper. The same orchestra
      you heard last night is to appear again to-day at&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We will go there, Lydia,&rdquo; he interrupted, and at once began to hum the
      gay little air that had so completely charmed him. &ldquo;Try it again, Lyddy.
      You'll get it in no time.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      After luncheon, like two happy children they rushed off to the concert,
      and it was not until they were on their way home at five o'clock that his
      enthusiasm began to wane. She was quick to detect the change. He became
      moody, preoccupied; his part of the conversation was kept up with an
      effort that lacked all of the spontaneity of his earlier and more engaging
      flights.
    </p>
    <p>
      They rode down town on the top of a Fifth Avenue stage, having it all to
      themselves. She found herself speculating on the change that had come over
      him, and soon lapsed into a reserve quite as pronounced as his own. By the
      time they were ready to get down at the corner above Brood's house there
      was no longer any pretence at conversation between them. The day's fire
      had burned out. Its glow had given way to the bleak, gray tone of dead
      coals.
    </p>
    <p>
      Lydia went far back in her calculations and attributed his mood to the
      promise she had exacted in regard to his attitude toward his father. It
      occurred to her that he was smarting under the restraint that promise
      involved. She realised now, more than ever before, that there could be no
      delay, no faltering on her part. She would have to see James Brood at
      once; go down on her knees to him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I feel rather guilty, Freddy,&rdquo; she said as they approached the house. &ldquo;Mr
      Brood will think it strange that I should plead a headache and yet run off
      to a concert and enjoy myself when he is so eager to finish the journal&mdash;especially
      as he is to sail so soon. I ought to see him; don't you think so? Perhaps
      there is something I can do to-night that will make up for the lost time.&rdquo;
       She was plainly nervous.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He'd work you to death if he thought it would serve his purpose,&rdquo; said
      Frederic gloomily. And back of that sentence lay the thought that made it
      absolutely imperative for her to act without delay.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I will go in for a few minutes,&rdquo; she said, at the foot of the steps. &ldquo;Are
      you not coming, too?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He had stopped. &ldquo;Not just now, Lyddy. I think I'll run up to Tom's flat
      and smoke a pipe with him. Thanks, old girl, for the happy day we've had.
      You don't mind if I leave you here?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Her heart gave a great throb of relief. It was best to have him out of the
      way for the time being.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, indeed,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;Do go and see Tom. I shan't be here long. We have
      had a glorious day, haven't we?&rdquo; There was something wistful in her smile
      as she held out her hand to him.
    </p>
    <p>
      He searched her face with tired, yearning eyes.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We have thousands of them ahead of us, Lyddy&mdash;days that will be all our
      own, with nothing else in them but ourselves. I&mdash;I wish we could
      begin them to-morrow, after all.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      A flush mounted to her cheek.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Good-bye, Freddy.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He seemed reluctant to release her hand; her hand was cold, but her eyes
      were shining with a glorious warmth.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&mdash;I may run in to see you this evening,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;You won't mind?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Come, by all means.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well&mdash;so-long,&rdquo; he said diffidently. &ldquo;So-long, Lyddy.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;So-long,&rdquo; she repeated, dropping into his manner of speech without
      thinking. There was a smothering sensation in her breast.
    </p>
    <p>
      He looked back as he strode off in the direction from which they had come.
      She was at the top of the steps, her finger on the electric button. He
      wondered why her face was so white. He had always thought of it as being
      full of colour, rich, soft, and warm.
    </p>
    <p>
      Inside the door Lydia experienced a strange sinking of the heart. Her
      limbs seemed curiously weak, and she was conscious of a feeling of utter
      loneliness, such as she had never known before. She looked about her in
      wonder, as if seeking an explanation for the extraordinary but fleeting
      impression that she was in a strange house. Never was she to find an
      interpretation of the queer fantasy that came and went almost in the span
      of a single breath.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Is Mr Brood at&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo; she began nervously.
    </p>
    <p>
      A voice at the top of the stairway interrupted the question she was
      putting to the footman.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Is it you, Lydia? Come up to my room.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The girl looked up and saw Mrs Brood leaning over the banister-rail. She
      was holding her pink dressing-gown closely about her throat, as if it had
      been hastily thrown about her shoulders. One bare arm was visible&mdash;completely
      so.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I came to see Mr Brood. Is he&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He is busy. Come up to my room,&rdquo; repeated Yvonne, somewhat imperiously.
    </p>
    <p>
      As Lydia mounted the stairs she had a fair glimpse of the other's face.
      Always pallid&mdash;but of a healthy pallor&mdash;it was now almost
      ghastly. Perhaps it was the light from the window that caused it; Lydia
      was not sure, but a queer greenish hue overspread the lovely, smiling
      face. The lips were red, very red&mdash;redder than she had ever seen them. The
      girl suddenly recalled the face she had once seen of a woman who was
      addicted to the drug habit.
    </p>
    <p>
      Mrs Brood met her at the top of the stairs. She was but half dressed. Her
      lovely neck and shoulders were now almost bare. Her hands were extended
      toward the visitor; the filmy lace gown hung loose and disregarded about
      her slim figure.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Come in, dear. Shall we have tea? I have been so lonely. One cannot read
      the books they print nowadays. Such stupid things, <i>ae?</i>&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She threw an arm about the tall girl, and Lydia was surprised to find that
      it was warm and full of a gentle strength. She felt her flesh tingle with
      the thrill of contact. Yes, it must have been the light from the window,
      for Yvonne's face was now aglow with the peculiar iridescence that was so
      peculiarly her own.
    </p>
    <p>
      A door closed softly on the floor above them. Mrs Brood glanced over her
      shoulder and upward. Her arm tightened perceptibly about Lydia's waist.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It was Ranjab,&rdquo; said the girl, and instantly was filled with amazement.
      She had not seen the Hindu, had not even been thinking of him, and yet she
      was impelled by some mysterious intelligence to give utterance to a
      statement in which there was conviction, not conjecture.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Did you see him?&rdquo; asked the other, looking at her sharply.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No,&rdquo; admitted Lydia, still amazed. &ldquo;I don't know why I said that.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Mrs Brood closed her boudoir door behind them. For an instant she stood
      staring at the knob, as if expecting to see it turn.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I know,&rdquo; she said, &ldquo;I know why you said it. Because it <i>was</i>
      Ranjab.&rdquo; She shivered slightly.
      &ldquo;I am afraid of that man, Lydia. He seems to be watching me all the time.
      Day and night his eyes seem to be upon me.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Why, should he be watching you?&rdquo; asked Lydia bluntly.
    </p>
    <p>
      Yvonne did not notice the question.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Even when I am asleep in my bed, in the dead hour of night, he is looking
      at me. I can feel it. Oh, it is not a dream, for my dreams are of
      something or someone else&mdash;never of him. And yet he is there, looking
      at me. It&mdash;it is uncanny.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Imagination,&rdquo; remarked Lydia quietly. &ldquo;He never struck me as especially
      omnipresent.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Didn't you <i>feel</i> him a moment ago?&rdquo; demanded Yvonne irritably.
    </p>
    <p>
      The other hesitated, reflecting.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I suppose it must have been something like that.&rdquo; They were still facing
      the door, standing close together. &ldquo;Why do you feel that he is watching
      you?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I don't know. I just feel it, that's all. Day and night. He can read my
      thoughts, Lydia, as he would read a book. Isn't&mdash;isn't it
      disgusting?&rdquo; Her laugh was spiritless, obviously artificial.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I shouldn't object to his reading my thoughts,&rdquo; said Lydia.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ah, but you are Lydia. It's different. I have thoughts sometimes, my
      dear, that would not&mdash;but there! Let us speak of more agreeable
      things. Take off your coat&mdash;here, let me help you. What a lovely
      waist! You will pardon my costume, won't you, or rather the lack of one?
      I shan't dress until dinner-time. Sit down here beside me. No tea? A
      cigarette, then. No?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I never smoke, you remember,&rdquo; said the other. She was looking at Yvonne
      now with a curious, new-found interest in her serious eyes. &ldquo;I came to
      explain to Mr Brood how it happens that&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Poof! Never explain, my dear, never explain anything to a man!&rdquo; cried
      Yvonne, lighting a cigarette. The flare of the match in the partially
      darkened room lit up her face with merciless candour. Lydia was conscious
      once more of the unusual pallor and a certain haggardness about the dark
      eyes.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But he is so eager to complete the&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Do you forgive me for what I said to you last night?&rdquo; demanded Yvonne,
      sitting down beside the girl on the <i>chaise longue</i>. The interruption
      was rude, perhaps, but it was impossible to resent it, so appealing was
      the expression in the offender's eyes.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It was so absurd, Mrs Brood, that I have scarcely given it a moment's
      thought. Of course, I was hurt at the time. It was so unjust to Mr Brood.
      It was&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It is like you to say that!&rdquo; cried Yvonne. &ldquo;You are splendid, Lydia. Will
      you believe me when I tell you that I love you&mdash;that I love you very
      dearly?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Lydia looked at her in some doubt, and not without misgivings.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I should like to believe it,&rdquo; she said noncommittally.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ah, but you doubt it. I see. Well, I do not blame you. I have given you
      much pain, much distress. When I am far away you will be glad&mdash;you will be
      happy. Is not that so?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But you are coming back,&rdquo; said Lydia with a frank smile, not meant to be
      unfriendly.
    </p>
    <p>
      Yvonne's face clouded.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, I shall probably come back. Nothing is sure in this queer world of
      ours.&rdquo; She threw her cigarette away. &ldquo;I don't like it to-day. Ugh! how it
      tastes in my mouth!&rdquo; She drew closer to the girl's side. Lydia's nostrils
      filled with the strange, sweet perfume that she affected, so individually
      hers, so personally Yvonne. &ldquo;Oh, yes; I shall come back. Why not? Is not
      this my home?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You may call it your home, Mrs Brood,&rdquo; said
      Lydia, &ldquo;but are you quite sure your thoughts always abide here? I mean in
      the United States, of course.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Yvonne had looked up at her quickly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, I see. No; I shall never be an American.&rdquo; Then she abruptly changed
      the subject. &ldquo;You have had a nice day with Frederic? You have been happy,
      both of you?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes&mdash;very happy, Mrs Brood,&rdquo; said the girl simply.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am glad. You must always be happy, you two. It is my greatest wish.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Lydia hesitated for a moment.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Frederic asked me to be his wife&mdash;to-morrow,&rdquo; she said, and her heart
      began to thump queerly. She felt that she was approaching a crisis of some
      sort.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;To-morrow?&rdquo; fell from Yvonne's lips. The word was drawn out, as if in one
      long breath. Then, to Lydia's astonishment, an extraordinary change came
      over the speaker.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, yes; it should be&mdash;it must be to-morrow. Poor boy&mdash;poor,
      poor boy! You will marry, yes, and go way at once, <i>ae?</i>&rdquo; Her voice
      was almost shrill in its intensity, her eyes were wide and eager and&mdash;anxious.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&mdash;&mdash;&mdash; Oh, Mrs Brood, is it for the best?&rdquo; cried Lydia.
      &ldquo;Is it the best thing for Frederic to do? I&mdash;I feared you might
      object. I am sure his father will refuse permission&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But you love each other&mdash;that is enough. Why ask the consent of
      anyone? Yes, yes, it is for the best. I know&mdash;oh, you cannot realise
      how well I know. You must not hesitate.&rdquo; The woman was trembling in her
      eagerness. Lydia's astonishment gave way to perplexity.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What do you mean? Why are you so serious&mdash;so intent on this&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Frederic has no money,&rdquo; pursued Yvonne, as if she had not heard Lydia's
      words. &ldquo;But that must not deter you&mdash;it must not stand in the way. I
      shall find a way; yes, I shall find a way. I&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Do you mean that you would provide for him for us?&rdquo; exclaimed Lydia.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;There is a way, there is a way,&rdquo; said the other, fixing her eyes
      appealingly on the girl's face, to which the flush of anger was slowly
      mounting.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;His father will not help him&mdash;if, that is what you are counting
      upon, Mrs Brood,&rdquo; said the girl coldly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I know. He will not help him; no.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Lydia started.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What do you know about&mdash;what has Mr Brood said to you?&rdquo; Her heart
      was cold with apprehension. &ldquo;Why are you going away next week? What has
      happened?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Brood's wife was regarding her with narrowing eyes.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Are you attributing my motives to something that my husband has said to
      me? Am I expected to say that he has&mdash;what you call it&mdash;that he
      has put his foot down?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am sorry you misunderstood my&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, I see now. You think my husband suspects that Frederic is too deeply
      interested in his beautiful stepmother; is not that so? Poof! It has
      nothing to do with it.&rdquo; Her eyes were sullen, full of resentment now. She
      was collecting herself.
    </p>
    <p>
      The girl's eyes expressed the disdain that suddenly took the place of
      apprehension in her thoughts. A sharp retort leaped to her lips, but she
      suppressed it.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Mr Brood does not like Frederic,&rdquo; she said instead, and could have cut
      out her tongue the instant the words were uttered. Yvonne's eyes were
      glittering with a light that she had never seen in them before. Afterward
      she described it to herself as baleful.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;So! He has spoken ill&mdash;evil&mdash;of his son to you?&rdquo; she said,
      almost in a monotone, &ldquo;He has hated him for years&mdash;is not that so? I
      am not the original cause, <i>ae?</i> It began long ago&mdash;long, long
      ago?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, I beg of you, Mrs Brood&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo; began
      Lydia, shrinking back in dismay.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You are free to speak your thoughts to me. I shall not be offended. What
      has he said to you about Frederic&mdash;and me?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nothing, I swear to you; nothing!&rdquo; cried the girl.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But you have the power of observation. You do not have to be told in so
      many words. You have been with him a great deal, alone. His manner tells
      you what his lips hold back. Tell me.&rdquo; Lydia resolved to take the plunge.
      Now was the time to speak plainly to this woman of the thing that was
      hurting her almost beyond the limits of endurance. Her voice was rather
      high-pitched. She had the fear that she would not be able to control it.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I should be blind not to have observed the cruel position in which you
      are placing Frederic. Is it surprising that your husband has eyes as well
      as I? What must be his thoughts, Mrs Brood?&rdquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      She expected an outburst, a
      torrent of indignation, an angry storm of words, and was therefore
      unprepared for the piteous, hunted expression that came swiftly into the
      lovely eyes, bent so appealing upon her own, which were cold and accusing.
      Here was a new phase to this extraordinary creature's character. She was a
      coward, after all, and Lydia despised a coward. The look of scorn deepened
      in her eyes, and out from her heart rushed all that was soft and tender in
      her nature, leaving it barren of all compassion.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I do not want to hurt Frederic,&rdquo; murmured
      Yvonne. &ldquo;I&mdash;I am sorry if&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You are hurting him dreadfully,&rdquo; said Lydia, suddenly choking up with
      emotion.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He is not&mdash;not in love with me,&rdquo; declared Yvonne,
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No,&rdquo; said the girl, regaining control of herself, &ldquo;he is not in love with
      you. That is the whole trouble. He is in love with me. But&mdash;but can't
      you see?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You are a wise young woman to know men so well,&rdquo; said the other
      enigmatically. &ldquo;I have never believed in St Anthony.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nor I,&rdquo; said Lydia, and was surprised at herself.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I prefer to put my faith in the women who tempted him,&rdquo; said Yvonne,
      drawing a little closer to the girl.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Perhaps you are right. They at least were not pretending.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am not so sure of that. At any rate, they succeeded in making a saint
      of him eventually.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I suppose you are undertaking a similar office in&mdash;in Frederic's
      behalf,&rdquo; said Lydia with fine irony.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Do you consider me to be a bad woman, Lydia?&rdquo; Her lips trembled. There
      was a suspicious quiver to her chin.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No; I do not,&rdquo; pronounced the girl flatly. &ldquo;If I could only think that of
      you it would explain everything, and I should know just how to treat you.
      But I do not think it of you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      With a long, deep sigh Yvonne crept closer and laid her head against
      Lydia's shoulder. The girl's body stiffened, her brow grew dark with
      annoyance.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am afraid you do not understand, Mrs Brood. The fact still remains that
      you have not considered Frederic's peace of mind.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nor yours,&rdquo; murmured the other.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nor mine,&rdquo; confessed Lydia, after a moment.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I did not know that you and Frederic were in love with each other until I
      had been here for some time,&rdquo; Mrs Brood explained, suddenly fretful.
    </p>
    <p>
      Lydia stared hard at the soft white cheek that lay exposed below the black
      crown of hair.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What had that to do with it?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;A great deal more than you can imagine,&rdquo; said the other, looking up into
      Lydia's face with a curious gleam in her eyes.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You admit, then, that you deliberately&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I admit nothing, except that I am sorry to have made you unhappy.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What kind of a woman are you?&rdquo; burst out Lydia's indignant soul. &ldquo;Have
      you no conception of the finer, nobler&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Yvonne deliberately put her hand over the girl's lips, checking the fierce
      outburst. She smiled rather plaintively as Lydia tried to jerk her head to
      one side in order to continue her reckless indictment.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You shall not say it, Lydia. I am not all that you think I am. No, no; a
      thousand times no. God pity me, I am more accursed than you may think with
      the finer and nobler instincts. If it were not so, do you think I should
      be where I am now&mdash;cringing here like a beaten child? No, you cannot
      understand&mdash;you never will understand. I shall say no more. It is
      ended. I swear on my soul that I did not know you were Frederic's
      sweetheart. I did not know&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But you knew almost immediately after you came here!&rdquo; exclaimed Lydia
      harshly. &ldquo;It is not myself I am thinking of, Mrs Brood, but of Frederic.
      Why have you done this abominable thing to him? Why?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&mdash;I did not realise what it would mean to him,&rdquo; said the other
      desperately. &ldquo;I&mdash;I did not count all the cost. But, dearest Lydia, it
      will come out all right. Everything shall be made right again, I promise
      you. I have made a horrible, horrible mistake. I can say no more. Now let
      me lie here with my head upon your breast. I want to feel the beating of
      your pure, honest heart&mdash;the heart I have hurt. I can tell by its
      throbs whether it will ever soften toward me. Do not say anything now&mdash;let
      us be still.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      It would be difficult to describe the feelings of
      Lydia Desmond as she sat there with the despised, though to be adored,
      head pillowed upon her breast, where it now rested in a sort of confident
      repose, as if there was safety in the very strength of the young girl's
      disapproval. Yvonne had twisted her lithe body on the <i>chaise longue</i>
      so that she half faced Lydia. Her free arm, from which the loose sleeve
      had fallen, leaving it bare to the shoulder, was about the girl's neck.
    </p>
    <p>
      For a long time Lydia stared straight before her, seeing nothing,
      positively dumb with wonder, and acknowledging a sense of dismay over her
      own disposition to submit to this extraordinary situation. She was asking
      herself why she did not cast the woman away, why she lacked the power to
      resent by deed as well as by thought.
    </p>
    <p>
      At last she lowered her eyes, conquered by an impulse she had resisted for
      many minutes. Her now perplexed gaze rested upon the gleaming white arm,
      and then moved wonderingly to the smooth cheek and throat. She saw the
      pulse beating in that slender neck. Fascinated, she watched it for a long,
      long time.
    </p>
    <p>
      Suddenly there ran through her heart a strange wave of tenderness. That
      faint, delicate throb in the throat of this woman represented the rush of
      life's blood&mdash;the warm, sweet flood of a lovely living thing.
      Yvonne's eyes were closed. The long, dark lashes lay feathery above the
      alabaster cheek; there were delicate blue lines in the lids. A faint,
      almost imperceptible depression as of pain appeared between the eyebrows.
      The black, glossy hair filled Lydia's nostrils with its living perfume.
    </p>
    <p>
      Life&mdash;marvellous, adorable life rested there on her breast. This
      woman had hurt her&mdash;had hurt her wantonly&mdash;and yet there came
      stealing over her, subtly, the conviction that she could never hurt her in
      return. She could never bring herself to the point of hurting this
      wondrous living, breathing, throbbing creature who pleaded, not only with
      her lips and eyes, but with the gentle heart-beats that rose and
      fell in her throat.
    </p>
    <p>
      Like velvet was the smooth, glossy skin of her arm and breast. Never had
      Lydia dreamed that flesh could be so soft and white and so aglow with
      vitality. There was a sheen to it, a soft sheen that seemed fairly to
      radiate light itself.
    </p>
    <p>
      Still in a maze of wonder and something bordering on sheer delight, she
      fell to studying the perfections that the cheek and lips revealed.
    </p>
    <p>
      Scarlet, pensively drooping were the lips, and almost opalescent the
      clear-cut cheek and chin. The delicate nostrils vibrated with the
      quickened breath that stirred the firm, full breast which rose and fell
      softly, gently; there were firm, hitherto invisible blue lines in the
      gleaming skin. Slowly, resistlessly Lydia's arm tightened about the
      slender, seductive body.
    </p>
    <p>
      After a long time, in which there was conflict, she suddenly pressed her
      warm lips to Yvonne's in a kiss that thrilled through every nerve in her
      body&mdash;a kiss that lingered because it was returned with equal fervour
      and abandon. They were clasped tightly in each other's arms and their eyes
      were closed as with pain.
    </p>
    <p>
      Then, in an abrupt revulsion of feeling, in a desperate awakening, Lydia
      relaxed. Her arms fell away from the warm, sweet body and her eyes widened
      with something that passed for confusion, but which was in reality shame.
      Almost roughly she pushed Yvonne away from her.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&mdash;I didn't mean to do that!&rdquo; she gasped.
    </p>
    <p>
      The other withdrew her arm and straightened up slowly, all the time
      regarding the girl with a strange, wondering look in her eyes&mdash;a look
      that quickly resolved itself into sadness so poignant that the girl, even
      in her confused state of mind, recognised it as such and was abashed.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I knew that you would,&rdquo; said Yvonne in a very low voice, and shook her
      head drearily.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am sorry,&rdquo; murmured Lydia in great distress.
    </p>
    <p>
      The other smiled, but it was a sad, plaintive effort on her part.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I knew that you would,&rdquo; she repeated.
    </p>
    <p>
      Lydia sprang to her feet, her face suddenly flaming with embarrassment.
      She felt unaccountably guilty of&mdash;she knew not what.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I must see Mr Brood. I stepped in to tell him that&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
       she began, trying to cover her confusion, but Yvonne interrupted.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I know that you could not help it, my dear,&rdquo; she said. Then, after a
      pause: &ldquo;You will let me know what my husband has to say about it?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;To&mdash;to say about it?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;About your decision to marry Frederic in spite of his objections.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Lydia felt a little shiver race over her as she looked toward the door.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You will help us?&rdquo; she said tremulously, turning to Yvonne. Again she saw
      the drawn, pained look about the dark eyes and was startled.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You can do more with him than I,&rdquo; was the response.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
