    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER XVI
    </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">L</span>ong past midnight
      the telephone in the Desmond apartment rang sharply, insistently. Lydia,
      who had just fallen asleep, awoke with a start and sat bolt upright in her
      bed. A clammy perspiration broke out all over her body. There in the
      darkness she shivered with a dread so desolating that every vestige of
      strength forsook her and she could only stare helplessly into the black
      pall that surrounded her.
    </p>
    <p>
      Never before in all her life had she been aroused from sleep by the
      jangling of a telephone-bell. The sound struck terror to her heart. She
      knew that something terrible had happened. She knew there had been a
      catastrophe.
    </p>
    <p>
      She sat there chattering until she heard her mother's door open and then
      the click of the receiver as it was lifted from the hook. Then she put her
      fingers to her ears and closed her eyes. The very worst had happened; she
      was sure of it. The blow had fallen. The one thought that seared her brain
      was that she had failed him, failed him miserably in the crisis. Oh, if
      she could only reclaim that lost hour of indecision and cowardice!
    </p>
    <p>
      The light in the hallway suddenly smote her in the face, and she realised
      for the first time that her eyes were tightly closed, as if to shut out
      some abhorrent sight.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Lydia!&rdquo; Her mother was standing in the open door. &ldquo;Oh, you are awake?&rdquo;
       Mrs Desmond stared in amazement at the girl's figure.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What is it, mother? Tell me what has happened? Is he&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He wants to speak to you. He is on the wire. His voice sounds queer&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The girl sprang out of bed and hurried to the telephone.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Don't go away, mother&mdash;stay here,&rdquo; she cried as she sped past the
      white-clad figure in the doorway. Mrs Desmond flattened herself against
      the wall and remained there as motionless as a statue, her sombre gaze
      fixed on her daughter's face.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, Frederic, it is I, Lydia. What is it, dear?&rdquo; Her voice was high and
      thin.
    </p>
    <p>
      His words came jerking over the wire, sharp and querulous. She closed her
      eyes in anticipation of the blow, her body rigid.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I'm sorry to disturb you,&rdquo; he was saying, &ldquo;but I just had to call you
      up.&rdquo; The words were disjointed, as if he forced them from his lips in a
      supreme effort at coherency.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, yes&mdash;it's all right. I don't mind. You did right. What is it?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I want you to release me from my promise.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Release you? Oh, Freddy!&rdquo; It was a wail that issued from her lips. Her
      body sagged limply, she steadied herself by leaning against the wall for
      support.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You've got to, Lydia. There's no other way. Something has happened
      to-night, dear. You've got to&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Has he&mdash;has he&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo; Her throat closed up as if
      gripped by a strong hand.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I'm sorry to drag you out of bed to tell you&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Freddy, Freddy!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;To tell you that I must withdraw my promise, even if you refuse to
      release me. Oh, I'm not excited, I'm not crazy, I'm not drunk! I never was
      so steady in my life. To-night has made a man of me. I know just where I
      stand at last. Now go back to bed, dearest, and don't worry about
      anything. I couldn't go ahead until I'd asked you to release me from the
      promise I made.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You mean&mdash;the promise&mdash;but, Freddy, I can't release you. I love
      you. I <i>will</i> be your wife, no matter what has happened, no matter&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, Lord, Lyddy&mdash;it isn't that! It's the other&mdash;the promise to
      say nothing to my father&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh!&rdquo; she sighed weakly, a vast wave of relief almost suffocating her.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He has made it impossible for me to go on without&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Where are you, Frederic?&rdquo; she cried in sudden alarm.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, I'm all right. I shan't go home, you may be sure of that. To-morrow
      will be time enough.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Where are you? I must know. How can I reach you by telephone&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Don't be frightened, dear. It's got to be, that's all. It might as well
      be ended now as later on. The last straw was laid on to-night. Now don't
      ask questions. I'll see you in the morning. Good night, sweetheart. I've&mdash;I've
      told you that I can't stick to my promise. You'll understand. I couldn't
      rest until I'd told you and heard your dear voice. Forgive me for calling
      you up. Tell your mother I'm sorry. Good night!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Freddy, listen to me! You must wait until I&mdash;&mdash;&mdash; Oh!&rdquo; He
      had hung up the receiver. She heard the whir of the open wire.
    </p>
    <p>
      There was little comfort for her in the hope held out by her mother as
      they sat far into the night and discussed the possibilities of the day so
      near at hand. She could see nothing but disaster, and she could think of
      nothing but her own lamentable weakness in shrinking from the encounter
      that might have made the present situation impossible. Between them mother
      and daughter constructed at random a dozen theories as to the nature of
      the fresh complication that had entered into the already serious
      situation, and always it was Lydia who advanced the most sickening of
      conjectures.
    </p>
    <p>
      Nor was it an easy matter for Mrs Desmond to combat these fears. In her
      heart she felt that an irreparable break had occurred and that the final
      clash was imminent. She tried to make light of the situation, however,
      prophesying a calmer attitude for Frederic after he had slept over his
      grievance, which, after all, she argued was doubtless exaggerated.
    </p>
    <p>
      She promised to go with Lydia to see James Brood in the morning, and to
      plead with him to be merciful to the boy she was to marry, no matter what
      transpired. The girl at first insisted on going over to see him that
      night, notwithstanding the hour, and was dissuaded only after the most
      earnest opposition.
    </p>
    <p>
      It was four o'clock before they went back to bed, and long after five
      before either closed her eyes.
    </p>
    <p>
      Mrs Desmond, utterly exhausted, was the first to awake. She glanced at the
      little clock on her dressing-table and gave a great start of
      consternation. It was long past nine o'clock. She arose at once and
      hurried to her daughter's door, half expecting to find the room empty and
      the girl missing from the apartment.
    </p>
    <p>
      But Lydia was lying there sound asleep. Mrs Desmond's lips parted to give
      voice to a gentle call, but it was never uttered. A feeling of infinite
      pity for the tired, harassed girl came over her. For a long time she stood
      there watching the gentle rise and fall of the sleeper's breast. Then she
      closed the door softly and stole back to her own room, inspired by a
      sudden resolve.
    </p>
    <p>
      While she was dressing the little maid-servant brought in her coffee and
      toast and received instructions not to awaken Miss Lydia but to let her
      have her sleep out. A few minutes later she left the apartment and walked
      briskly around the corner to Brood's home.
    </p>
    <p>
      She had resolved to take the matter out of her daughter's hands. As she
      stood at the bedroom door watching Lydia's sweet, troubled face, there
      arose within her the mother instinct to fight for her young. It was not
      unlikely that James Brood could be moved by Lydia's pleading, in spite of
      his declaration that Frederic should never marry her, but the mother
      recognised the falseness of a position gained by such means.
    </p>
    <p>
      Over Lydia's head would hang the perpetual reminder that he had submitted
      out of consideration for her, and not through fairness or justice to
      Frederic; all the rest of her life she would be made to feel that he
      tolerated Frederic for her sake. The girl would never know a moment in
      which she could be free from that ugly sense of obligation. God willing,
      Frederic would be her daughter's husband. Lydia might spare him the blow
      that James Brood could deal, but all of her life would be spent in
      contemplation of that one bitter hour in which she went on her knees to
      beg for mercy.
    </p>
    <p>
      The mother saw all this with a foresightedness that stripped the situation
      of every vestige of romance. Lydia might rejoice at the outset, but there
      would surely come a time of heartache for her. It would come with the full
      realisation that James Brood's pity was hard to bear.
    </p>
    <p>
      Fearing that she might be too late, she walked so rapidly that she was
      quite out of breath when she entered the house. Mr Riggs and Mr Dawes were
      putting on their coats in the hall preparatory to their short morning
      constitutional. They greeted her profusely, and with one accord proceeded
      to divest themselves of the coats, announcing in one voice their intention
      to remain for a good, old-fashioned chat.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It's dear of you,&rdquo; she said hurriedly, &ldquo;but I must see Mr Brood at once.
      Why not come over to my apartment this afternoon for a cup of tea and&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Mrs Brood's voice interrupted her.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What do you want, Mrs Desmond?&rdquo; came from the landing above.
    </p>
    <p>
      The visitor looked up with a start, not so much of surprise as uneasiness.
      There was something sharp, unfriendly, in the low, level tones.
    </p>
    <p>
      Yvonne, fully dressed&mdash;a most unusual circumstance at that hour of
      the day&mdash;was leaning over the banister-rail.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I came to see Mr Brood on a very important&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He is occupied. Won't I do as well?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It is really quite serious, Mrs Brood. I am afraid it would be of no
      avail to&mdash;to take it up with you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Have you been sent here by someone else?&rdquo; demanded Mrs Brood.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I have not seen Frederic,&rdquo; fell from the other's lips before she thought.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I dare say you haven't,&rdquo; said the other with ominous clearness. &ldquo;He has
      been here since seven this morning, waiting for a chance to speak to his
      father in private.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Heaven help me! I&mdash;I am too&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Unless he spent the night in your apartment, I fancy you haven't seen
      him,&rdquo; went on Yvonne languidly.
    </p>
    <p>
      She was descending the stairs slowly, almost lazily as she uttered the
      remark.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;They are together now?&rdquo; gasped Mrs Desmond.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Will you come into the library? Good morning, gentlemen. I trust you may
      enjoy your long walk.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Mrs Desmond followed her into the library. Yvonne closed the door almost
      in the face of Mr Riggs, who had opened his mouth to accept the invitation
      to tea, but who said he'd &ldquo;be blasted&rdquo; instead, so narrow was his escape
      from having his nose banged. He emphasised the declaration by shaking his
      fist at the door.
    </p>
    <p>
      The two women faced each other. For the first time since she had known
      Yvonne Brood, Mrs Desmond observed a high touch of colour in her cheeks.
      Her beautiful eyes were alive with an excitement she could not conceal.
      Neither spoke for a moment.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You are accountable for this, Mrs Brood,&rdquo; said Lydia Desmond's mother
      sternly, accusingly. She expected a storm of indignant protest. Instead,
      Yvonne smiled slightly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It will not hurt my husband to discover that Frederic is a man and not a
      milksop,&rdquo; she said, but despite her coolness there was a perceptible note
      of anxiety in her voice.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You know, then, that they are&mdash;that they will quarrel?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I fancy it was in Frederic's mind to do so when he came here this
      morning. He was still in his evening clothes, Mrs Desmond.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Where are they now?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I think he has them on,&rdquo; said Yvonne lightly.
    </p>
    <p>
      Mrs Desmond regarded her for a moment in perplexity. Then her eyes flashed
      dangerously.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I do not think you misunderstood me, Mrs Brood. Where are Frederic and
      his father?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am not accustomed to that tone of voice, Mrs Desmond.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am no longer your housekeeper,&rdquo; said the other succinctly. &ldquo;You do not
      realise what this quarrel may mean. I insist on going up to them before it
      has gone too far.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;My husband can take care of himself, thank you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am not thinking of your husband, but of that poor boy who is&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And if I am to judge by Frederic's manner this morning, he is also able
      to take care of himself,&rdquo; said Yvonne coolly. Her voice shook a little.
    </p>
    <p>
      Mrs Desmond shot a quick glance of comprehension at the speaker.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You are worried, Mrs Brood. Your manner betrays you. I command you to
      tell me how long they have been upstairs together. How long&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Will you be so good, Mrs Desmond, as to leave this house instantly?&rdquo;
       cried Yvonne angrily.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No,&rdquo; said the other quietly. &ldquo;I suppose I am too late to prevent trouble
      between those two men, but I shall at least remain here to assure Frederic
      of my sympathy, to help him if I can, to offer him the shelter of my
      home.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      A spasm of alarm crossed Yvonne's face.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Do you really believe it will come to that?&rdquo; she demanded nervously.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;If what I fear should come to pass, he will not stay in this house
      another hour. He will go forth from it cursing James Brood with all the
      hatred that his soul can possess. And now, Mrs Brood, shall I tell you
      what I think of you?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No. It isn't at all necessary. Besides, I've changed my mind. I'd like
      you to remain. I do not want to mystify you any farther, Mrs Desmond, but
      I now confess to you that I am losing my courage. Don't ask me to tell you
      why, but&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I suppose it is the custom with those who play with fire. They shrink
      when it burns them.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Mrs Brood looked at her steadily. The rebellious, sullen expression died
      out of her eyes. She sighed deeply, almost despairingly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am sorry you think ill of me, but yet I cannot blame you for
      considering me to be a&mdash;a&mdash;&mdash;&mdash; I'll not say it. Mrs
      Desmond, I&mdash;I wish I had never come to this house.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Permit me to echo your words.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You will never be able to understand me. And, after all, why should I
      care? You are nothing to me. You are merely a good woman who has no real
      object in life. You&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No real object in life?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Precisely. Sit down. We will wait here together, if you please. I&mdash;I
      <i>am</i> worried. I think I rather like to feel that you are here with
      me. You see, the crisis has come.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You know, of course, that he turned one wife out of this house, Mrs
      Brood,&rdquo; said Mrs Desmond deliberately.
    </p>
    <p>
      Something like terror leaped into the other's eyes. The watcher
      experienced an incomprehensible feeling of pity for her&mdash;she who had
      been despising her so fiercely the instant before.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He&mdash;he will not turn me out,&rdquo; murmured Yvonne, and suddenly began
      pacing the floor, her hands clenched. Stopping abruptly in front of the
      other woman, she exclaimed: &ldquo;He made a great mistake in driving that other
      woman out. He is not likely to repeat it, Mrs Desmond.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes&mdash;I think he <i>did</i> make a mistake,&rdquo; said Mrs Desmond calmly.
      &ldquo;But he does not think so. He is a man of iron. He is unbending.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He is a wonderful man&mdash;a great, splendid man,&rdquo; cried Yvonne
      fiercely. &ldquo;It is I&mdash;Yvonne Lestrange&mdash;who proclaim it to the
      world. I cannot bear to see him suffer. I&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Then, why do you&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ah, you would say it, eh? Well, there is no answer. Poof! Perhaps it will
      not be so bad as we think. Come! I am no longer uneasy. See! I am very
      calm. Am I not an example for you? Sit down. We will wait together.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      They sat far apart, each filled with dark misgivings, though radically
      opposed in their manner of treating the situation. Mrs Desmond was cold
      with apprehension. She sat immovable, tense. Yvonne sank back easily in a
      deep, comfortable chair and coolly lighted a cigarette. It would have been
      remarked by a keen observer that her failure to offer one to her visitor
      was evidence of an unwonted abstraction. As a matter of fact, inwardly she
      was trembling like a leaf.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I suppose there is nothing to do,&rdquo; said Mrs Desmond in despair, after a
      long silence. &ldquo;Poor Lydia will never forgive herself.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Yvonne blew rings of smoke toward the ceiling.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I dare say you think I am an evil person, Mrs Desmond.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Curiously, Mrs Brood, I have never thought of you in that light. Your
      transgressions are the greater for that reason.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Transgressions? An amiable word, believe me.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I did not come here, however, to discuss your actions.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Yvonne leaned forward suddenly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You do not ask what transpired last night to bring about this crisis. Why
      do you hesitate?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Mrs Desmond shook her head slowly. &ldquo;I do not want to know.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, it was not what you have been thinking it was,&rdquo; said Yvonne
      levelly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am relieved to hear it,&rdquo; said the other rather grimly.
    </p>
    <p>
      Mrs Brood flushed to the roots of her hair.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I do not want to appear unfair to my husband, but I declare to you, Mrs
      Desmond, that Frederic is fully justified in the attitude he has taken
      this morning. His father humiliated him last night in a manner that made
      forbearance impossible. That much I must say for Frederic. And permit me
      to add, from my soul, that he is vastly more sinned against than sinning.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I can readily believe that, Mrs Brood.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;This morning Frederic came into the breakfast-room while we were having
      our coffee. You look surprised. Yes, I was having breakfast with my
      husband. I knew that Frederic would come. That was my reason. When I heard
      him in the hall I sent the servants out of the dining-room. He had spent
      the night with a friend. His first words on entering the room were these&mdash;I
      shall never forget them: 'Last night I thought I loved you, father, but I
      have come home just to tell you that I hate you. I can't stay in this
      house another day. I'm going to get out. But I just wanted you to know
      that I thought I loved you last night, as a son should love his father. I
      just wanted you to know it.'
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He did not even look at me, Mrs Desmond. I don't believe he knew I was
      there. I shall never forget the look in James Brood's face. It was as if
      he saw a ghost or some horrible thing that fascinated him. He did not
      utter a word, but stared at Frederic in that terrible, awe-struck way.
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;'I'm going to get out,' said Frederic, his voice rising. 'You've treated
      me like a dog all of my life, and I'm through. I shan't even say good-bye
      to you. You don't deserve any more consideration from me than I've
      received from you. I hope I'll never see you again. If I ever have a son
      I'll not treat him as you've treated your son. You don't deserve the
      honour of being called father; you don't deserve to have a son. I wish to
      God I had never been obliged to call you father! I don't know what you did
      to my mother, but if you treated her as&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;'
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Just then my husband found his voice. He sprang to his feet, and I've
      never seen such a look of rage. I thought he was going to strike Frederic,
      and I think I screamed&mdash;just a little scream, of course. I was so
      terrified. But he only said&mdash;and it was horrible the way he said
      it&mdash;'You fool&mdash;you bastard!' And Frederic laughed in his face and cried out,
      unafraid: 'I'm glad you call me a bastard! I'd rather be one than be your
      son. It would at least give me something to be proud of&mdash;a real father!'&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Good Heaven!&rdquo; fell from Mrs Desmond's white lips.
    </p>
    <p>
      Yvonne seemed to have paused to catch her breath. Her breast heaved
      convulsively, the grip of her hands tightened on the arms of the chair.
    </p>
    <p>
      Suddenly she resumed her recital, but her voice was hoarse and tremulous.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I was terribly frightened. I thought of calling out to Jones, but I&mdash;I
      had no voice! Ah, you have never seen two angry men waiting to spring at
      each other's throats, Mrs Desmond. My husband suddenly regained control of
      himself. He was very calm. 'Come with me,' he said to Frederic. 'This is
      not the place to wash our filthy family linen. You say you want something
      to be proud of. Well, you shall have your wish. Come to my study.' And
      they went away together, neither speaking a word to me&mdash;they did not
      even glance in my direction. They went up the stairs. I heard the door
      close behind them&mdash;away up there. That was half an hour ago. I have
      been waiting, too&mdash;waiting as you are waiting now&mdash;to comfort
      Frederic when he comes out of that room a wreck.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Mrs Desmond started up, an incredulous look in her eyes.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You are taking his side? You are against your husband? Oh, now I know the
      kind of woman you are. I know&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Peace! You do not know the kind of woman I am. You will never know. Yes,
      I shall take sides with Frederic.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You do not love your husband!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      A strange, unfathomable smile came into Yvonne's face and stayed there.
      Mrs Desmond experienced the same odd feeling she had had years ago on
      first seeing the Sphinx. She was suddenly confronted by an unsolvable
      mystery.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He shall not drive me out of his house, Mrs Desmond,&rdquo; was her answer to
      the challenge.
    </p>
    <p>
      A door slammed in the upper regions of the house. Both women started to
      their feet.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It is over,&rdquo; breathed Yvonne with a tremulous sigh.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We shall see how well they were able to take care of themselves, Mrs
      Brood,&rdquo; said Mrs Desmond in a low voice.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We shall see&mdash;yes,&rdquo; said the other mechanically. Suddenly she turned
      on the tall, accusing figure beside her. &ldquo;Go away! Go now! I command you
      to go. This is <i>our</i> affair, Mrs Desmond. You are not needed here.
      You were too late, as you say. I beg of you, go!&rdquo; She strode swiftly
      toward the door. As she was about to place her hand on the knob it was
      opened from the other side, and Ranjab stood before them.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;<i>Sahib</i> begs to be excused, Mrs Desmond. He is just going out.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Going out?&rdquo; cried Yvonne, who had shrunk back into the room.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, <i>sahibah</i>. You will please excuse, Mrs Desmond. He regret very
      much.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Mrs Desmond passed slowly through the door, which he held open for her. As
      she passed by the Hindu she looked full into his dark, expressive eyes,
      and there was a question in hers. He did not speak, but she read the
      answer as if it were on a printed page. Her shoulders drooped.
    </p>
    <p>
      She went back to Lydia.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <a name="link2HCH0017" id="link2HCH0017"> </a>
    </p>
    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER XVII
    </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">W</span>hen James Brood
      and Frederic left the dining-room, nearly an hour prior to the departure of
      Mrs Desmond, there was in the mind of each the resolution to make short
      work of the coming interview. Each knew that the time had arrived for the
      parting of the ways, and neither had the least desire to prolong the
      suspense.
    </p>
    <p>
      Frederic, far from suspecting the ordeal in store for him, experienced a
      curious sense of exaltation as he followed the master of the house up the
      stairway. He was about to declare his freedom; the very thought of it
      thrilled him. He had at last found the courage to revolt, and there was
      cause for rejoicing in the prospect of a lively triumph over what he was
      pleased to call oppression.
    </p>
    <p>
      He would not mince matters! Oh, no; he would come straight to the point.
      There wasn't any sense in temporising. There were years of pent-up
      grievances that he could fling at his father, but he would crystallise
      them into a few withering minutes and have done with the business. He knew
      he was as pale as a ghost and his legs were strangely weak, but he was not
      cognisant of the slightest sensation of fear, nor the least inclination to
      shrink from the consequences of that brief, original challenge.
    </p>
    <p>
      The study door was closed. James Brood put his hand on the knob, but
      before turning it faced the young man with an odd mixture of anger and
      pity in his eyes.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Perhaps it will be better if we had nothing more to say to each other,&rdquo;
       he said with an effort.
      &ldquo;I have changed my mind. I cannot say the thing to you that I&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Has it got anything to do with Yvonne and me?&rdquo; demanded Frederic
      ruthlessly, jumping at conclusions in his new-found arrogance.
    </p>
    <p>
      Brood threw open the door.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Step inside,&rdquo; he said in a voice that should have warned the younger man,
      it was so prophetic of disaster. Frederic had touched the open sore with
      that unhappy question. Not until this instant had James Brood admitted to
      himself that there was a sore and that it had been festering all these
      weeks. Now it was laid bare and it smarted with pain. Nothing could save
      Frederic after that reckless, deliberate thrust at the very core of the
      malignant growth that lay so near the surface.
    </p>
    <p>
      It had been in James Brood's heart to spare the boy. An unaccountable wave
      of compassion had swept through him as he mounted the stairs, leading his
      victim to the sacrifice. He would have allowed him to go his way in
      ignorance of the evil truth; he would have spared the son of Matilde and
      been happier, far happier, he knew, for having done so. He would have let
      him fare forth, as he elected to go, rejoicing in his foolish
      independence, scorning to the end of his days, perhaps, the man who posed
      as father to him.
    </p>
    <p>
      But Frederic had touched the hateful sore. His chance was gone.
    </p>
    <p>
      Hot words were on Frederic's lips. Brood held up his hand, and there was
      in the gesture a command that silenced the young man. He was somewhat
      shocked to find that he still recognised the other's right to command. The
      older man went quickly to the door of the Hindu's closet. He rapped on the
      panel, and in an instant the door was opened. Ranjab stepped out and
      quickly closed the door behind him. A few words, spoken in lowered tones
      and in the language of the East, passed between master and man.
    </p>
    <p>
      Frederic turned his back to them. Moved by a sudden impulse, he strode to
      the window and pulled the curtains apart. A swift glance upward showed him
      the drawn shades in Lydia's bedroom windows. Somehow he was glad that she
      was asleep. An impulse as strong as the other ordered him to shift his
      glance downward to the little balcony outside of Yvonne's windows. Then he
      heard the door close softly behind him and turned to face his father.
    </p>
    <p>
      They were alone in the room. He squared his shoulders.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I suppose you think I am in love with her,&rdquo; he said defiantly. He waited
      a moment for the response that did not come. Brood was regarding him with
      eyes from which every spark of compassion had disappeared. &ldquo;Well, it may
      interest you to know that I intend to marry Lydia this very day.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Brood advanced a few steps toward him. In the subdued light of the room
      his features were not clearly distinguishable. His face was gray and
      shadowy; only the eyes were sharply defined. They glowed like points of
      light, unflickering.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I shall be sorry for Lydia,&rdquo; he said levelly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You needn't be,&rdquo; said Frederic hotly. &ldquo;She understands everything.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You were born to be dishonest in love.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What do you mean by that?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It is my purpose to tell you precisely what I mean. Lydia understands far
      more than you think. If she marries you it will be with her eyes open; she
      will have no one to blame but herself for the mistake.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, I haven't tried to deceive her as to my prospects. She knows how poor
      we will be at the&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Does she know that this love you profess for her is at the very outset
      disloyal?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Frederic was silent for a moment. A twinge shot through his heart.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;She understands everything,&rdquo; he repeated stubbornly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Have you lied to her?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Lied? You'd better be careful how you&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Have you told her that you love her and no one else?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Certainly!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Then you <i>have</i> lied to her.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      There was silence&mdash;tense silence.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Do you expect me to strike you for that?&rdquo; came at last from Frederic's
      lips, low and menacing.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You have always considered yourself to be my son, haven't you?&rdquo; pursued
      Brood deliberately. &ldquo;Can you say to me that you have behaved of late as a
      son should&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Wait! We'll settle that point right now. I <i>did</i> lose my head. Head,
      I say, not heart. I shan't attempt to explain&mdash;I can't, for that
      matter. As for Yvonne&mdash;well, she's as good as gold. She understands
      me far better than I understand myself. She knows that even honest men
      lose their heads sometimes&mdash;and she knows the difference between love
      and&mdash;the other thing. I can say to you now that I would sooner have
      cut my own throat than do more than envy you the possession of someone you
      do not deserve. I <i>have</i> considered myself your son. I have no
      apology to make for my&mdash;we'll call it infatuation. I shall only admit
      that it has existed and that I have despaired. So God is my witness, I
      have never loved anyone but Lydia. I have given her pain, and the amazing
      part of it is that I can't help myself. Naturally, you can't understand
      what it all means. You are not a young man any longer. You cannot
      understand.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Good God!&rdquo; burst from Brood's lips. Then he laughed aloud&mdash;grotesquely.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yvonne is the most wonderful thing that has ever come into my life. She
      has shown me that life is beautiful and rich and full of warmth. I had
      always thought it ugly and cold. Something inside of me awoke the instant
      I looked into her eyes&mdash;something that had always been there, and yet
      undeveloped. She spoke to me with her eyes, if you can believe such a
      thing possible, and I understood. I adored her the instant I saw her. I
      have felt sometimes that I knew her a thousand years ago. I have felt that
      I loved her a thousand years ago.&rdquo; A calm seriousness now attended his
      speech, in direct contrast to the violent mood that had gone before. &ldquo;I
      have thought of little else but her. I confess it to you. But through it
      all there has never been an instant in which I did not worship Lydia
      Desmond. I&mdash;I do not pretend to account for it. It is beyond me.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Brood waited patiently to the end.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Your mother before you had a somewhat similar affliction,&rdquo; he said, still
      in the steady, repressed voice. &ldquo;Perhaps it is a gift&mdash;a convenient
      gift&mdash;this ability to worship without effort.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Better leave my mother out of it,&rdquo; said Frederic sarcastically. A look of
      wonder leaped to his eyes. &ldquo;That's the first time you've condescended to
      acknowledge that I ever had a mother.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I shall soon make you regret that you were ever so blessed as to have had
      one.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You've always made it easy for me to regret that I ever had a father.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Brood's smile was deadly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;If you have anything more to say to me, you had better get it over. Purge
      your soul of all the gall that embitters it. I grant you that privilege.
      Take your innings.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      A spasm of pain crossed Frederic's face.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, I am entitled to my innings. I'll go back to what I said downstairs.
      I thought I loved and honoured you last night. I would have forgiven
      everything if you had granted me a friendly&mdash;friendly, that's all&mdash;just
      a friendly word. You denied&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I suppose you want me to believe that it was love for me that brought you
      slinking to the theatre,&rdquo; said the other ironically.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I don't expect you to believe anything. I was lonely. I wanted to be with
      you and Yvonne. Curse you! Can't you understand how lonely I've been all
      my life? Can't you understand how hungry I am for the affection that every
      other boy I've known has had from his parents? I've never asked you about
      my mother. I used to wonder a good deal. Every other boy had a mother. I
      never had one. I couldn't understand it. And they all had fathers, but
      they were not like my father. Their fathers were kind and loving, they
      were interested in everything their sons did&mdash;good or bad. I used to
      love the fathers of all those other lucky boys at school. They came often&mdash;and
      so did the mothers. No one ever came to see me&mdash;no one!
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I used to wonder why you never told me of my own mother. Long ago I gave
      up wondering. Something warned me not to ask you about her. Something told
      me it was best to let sleeping dogs lie. I never inquired of anyone after
      I was old enough to think for myself. I was afraid to ask, so I waited,
      hoping all the time that you would some day tell me of her. But you've
      never breathed her name to me. I no longer wonder. I know now that she
      must have hated you with all the strength of her soul. God, how she must
      have hated to feel the touch of your hands upon her body! Something tells
      me she left you, and if she did, I hope she afterward found someone who&mdash;but
      no, I won't say it. Even now I haven't the heart to hurt you by saying
      that.&rdquo; He stopped, choking up with the rush of bitter words. &ldquo;Well, why
      don't you say something?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I'm giving you your innings. Go on,&rdquo; said Brood softly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;She must have loved you once&mdash;or she wouldn't have married you. She
      must have loved you or I wouldn't be here in this world. She&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ha!&rdquo; came sharply from Brood.
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&mdash;didn't find you out until it was
      too late. She was lovely, I know. She was sweet and gentle and she loved
      happiness. I can see that in her face, in her big, wistful eyes. You&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What's this?&rdquo; demanded Brood, startled. &ldquo;What are you saying?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, I've got her portrait&mdash;an old photograph. For a month I've
      carried it here in this pocket-case over my heart. I wouldn't part
      with it for all the money in the world. When I look at the dear, sweet,
      girlish face and her eyes look back into mine, I know that <i>she</i>
      loved me.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Her portrait?&rdquo; said Brood, unbelieving.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes&mdash;and I have only to look at it to know that she couldn't have
      hurt you&mdash;so it must have been the other way round. She's dead now, I
      know, but she didn't die for years after I was born. Why was it that I
      never saw her? Why was I kept up there in that damnable village&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Where did you get that photograph?&rdquo; demanded Brood hoarsely. &ldquo;Where, I
      say? What interfering fool&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I wouldn't be too nasty, if I were you,&rdquo; said Frederic, a note of triumph
      in his voice. &ldquo;Yvonne gave it to me. I made her promise to say nothing to
      you about it. She&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yvonne? Are you&mdash;&mdash;&mdash; Impossible! She could not have had&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It was lying under the marble top of that old bureau in her bedroom. She
      found it there when the men came to take it away to storage. It hadn't
      been moved in twenty years or more.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;In&mdash;her&mdash;bedroom?&rdquo; murmured Brood, passing his hand over his
      eyes. &ldquo;The old bureau&mdash;marble top&mdash;good Lord! It was our
      bedroom. Let me see it&mdash;give it to me this instant!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I can't do that. It's mine now. It's safe where it is.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yvonne found it? Yvonne? And gave it to you? What damnable trick of fate
      is this? But&mdash;&mdash;&mdash; Ah, it may not be a portrait of your&mdash;your
      mother. Some old photograph that got stuck under the&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No; it is my mother. Yvonne saw the resemblance at once and brought it to
      me. And it may interest you to know that she advised me to treasure it all
      my life, because it would always tell me how lovely and sweet my mother
      was&mdash;the mother I have never seen.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I insist on seeing that picture,&rdquo; said Brood with deadly intensity.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No,&rdquo; said Frederic, folding his arms tightly across his breast. &ldquo;You
      didn't deserve her then and you&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You don't know what you are saying, boy!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ah, don't I? Well, I've got just a little bit of my mother safe here over
      my heart&mdash;a little faded card, that's all&mdash;and you shall not rob
      me of that. I wish to God I had her here, just as she was when she had the
      picture taken. Don't glare at me like that. I don't intend to give it up.
      Last night I was sorry for you. I had the feeling that somehow you have
      always been unhappy over something that happened in the past, and that my
      mother was responsible. And yet when I took out this photograph, this tiny
      bit of old cardboard&mdash;see, it is so small that it can be carried in
      my waistcoat pocket&mdash;when I took it out and looked at the pure,
      lovely face, I&mdash;by Heaven, I knew she was not to blame!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Have you finished?&rdquo; asked Brood, wiping his brow. It was dripping.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Except to repeat that I am through with you for ever. I've had all that I
      can endure, and I'm through. My greatest regret is that I didn't get out
      long ago. But like a fool&mdash;a weak fool&mdash;I kept on hoping that
      you'd change and that there were better days ahead for me. I kept on
      hoping that you'd be a real father to me. Good Lord, what a libel on the
      name!&rdquo; He laughed raucously. &ldquo;I'm sick of calling you father. You did me
      the honour downstairs of calling me 'bastard.' You had no right to call me
      that; but, by Heaven, if it were not for this bit of cardboard here over
      my heart, I'd laugh in your face and be happy to shout from the housetops
      that I am no son of yours. But there's no such luck as that! I've only to
      look at my mother's innocent, soulful face to&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Stop!&rdquo; shouted Brood in an awful voice. His clenched hands were raised
      above his head. &ldquo;The time has come for me to tell you the truth about this
      innocent mother of yours. Luck is with you. I am not your father. You are&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Wait! If you are going to tell me that my mother was not a good woman, I
      want to go on record in advance of anything you may say, as being glad
      that I am her son no matter who my father was. I am glad that she loved me
      because I was her child, and if you are not my father, then I still have
      the joy of knowing that she loved some one man well enough to&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
       He broke off the bitter sentence and with nervous fingers drew a small
      leather case from his waistcoat pocket. &ldquo;Before you go any farther, take
      one look at her face. It will make you ashamed of yourself. Can you stand
      there and lie about her after looking into&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He was holding the window curtains apart, and a stream of light fell upon
      the lovely face, so small that Brood was obliged to come quite close to be
      able to see it. His eyes were distended.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It is not Matilde&mdash;it is like her, but&mdash;yes, yes; it is
      Matilde! I must be losing my mind to have thought&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo; He
      wiped his brow. &ldquo;But it was startling&mdash;positively uncanny.&rdquo; He spoke
      as to himself, apparently forgetting that he had a listener.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, can you lie about her now?&rdquo; demanded Frederic.
    </p>
    <p>
      Brood was still staring, as if fascinated, at the tiny photograph.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But I have never seen that picture before. She never had one so small as
      that. It&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It was made in Vienna,&rdquo; interrupted Frederic, not without a strange
      thrill of satisfaction in his soul, &ldquo;and before you were married, I'd say.
      On the back of it is written 'To my own sweetheart,' in Hungarian, Yvonne
      says. There! Look at her. She was like that when you married her. How
      adorable she must have been. 'To my own sweetheart'! O&mdash;ho!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      A hoarse cry of rage and pain burst from Brood's lips. The world grew red
      before his eyes.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;'To my own sweetheart'!&rdquo; he cried out. He sprang forward and struck the
      photograph from Frederic's hand. It fell to the floor at his feet. Before
      the young man could recover from his surprise, Brood's foot was upon the
      bit of cardboard. &ldquo;Don't raise your hand to me! Don't you dare to strike
      me! Now I shall tell you who that sweetheart was!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Half an hour later James Brood descended the stairs alone. He went
      straight to the library, where he knew that he could find Yvonne. Ranjab,
      standing in the hall, peered into his white, drawn face as he passed, and
      started forward as if to speak to him. But Brood did not see him. He did
      not lift his gaze from the floor. The Hindu went swiftly up the stairs, a
      deep dread in his soul.
    </p>
    <p>
      The shades were down. Brood stopped inside the door and looked dully about
      the library. He was on the point of retiring when Yvonne spoke to him out
      of the shadowy corner beyond the fireplace.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Close the door,&rdquo; she said huskily. Then she emerged slowly, almost like a
      spectre, from the dark background formed by the huge mahogany bookcases
      that lined the walls from floor to ceiling. &ldquo;You were a long time up
      there,&rdquo; she went on.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Why is it so dark in here, Yvonne?&rdquo; he asked lifelessly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;So that it would not be possible for me to see the shame in your eyes,
      James.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He leaned heavily against the long table. She came up and stood across the
      table from him, and he felt that her eyes were searching his very soul.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I have hurt him beyond all chance of recovery,&rdquo; he said hoarsely.
    </p>
    <p>
      She started violently.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You&mdash;you struck him down? He&mdash;he is dying?&rdquo; Her voice trailed
      off into a whisper.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He will be a long time in dying. It will be slow. I struck him down, not
      with my hand, not with a weapon that he could parry, but with words&mdash;words!
      Do you hear? I have crushed his soul with words!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, you coward!&rdquo; she cried, leaning over the table, her eyes blazing. &ldquo;I
      can understand it in you. You have no soul of your own. What have you done
      to your son, James Brood?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He drew back as if from the impact of a blow. &ldquo;Coward? If I have crushed
      his soul, it was done in time, Yvonne, to deprive you of the glory of
      doing it.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What did he say to you about me?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You have had your fears for nothing. He did not put you in jeopardy,&rdquo; he
      said scornfully.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I know. He is not a coward,&rdquo; she said calmly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;In your heart you are reviling me. You judge me as one guilty soul judges
      another. Suppose that I were to confess to you that I left him up there
      with all the hope, all the life blasted out of his eyes&mdash;with a wound
      in his heart that will never stop bleeding&mdash;that I left him because I
      was sorry for what I had done and could not stand by and look upon the
      wreck I had created. Suppose&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am still thinking of you as a coward. What is it to me that you are
      sorry now? What have you done to that wretched, unhappy boy?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He will tell you soon enough. Then you will despise me even more than I
      despise myself. He&mdash;he looked at me with his mother's eyes when I kept on
      striking blows at his very soul. Her eyes&mdash;eyes that were always pleading
      with me! But, curse them&mdash;always scoffing at me! For a moment I
      faltered. There was a wave of love&mdash;yes, love, not pity, for him&mdash;as
      I saw him go down before the words I hurled at him. It was as if I had
      hurt the only thing in all the world that I love. Then it passed. He was
      not meant for me to love. He was born for me to despise. He was born to
      torture me as I have tortured him.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You poor fool!&rdquo; she cried, her eyes glittering.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sometimes I have doubted my own reason,&rdquo; he went on, as if he had not
      heard her scathing remark. &ldquo;Sometimes I have felt a queer gripping of the
      heart when I was harshest toward him. Sometimes, his eyes&mdash;<i>her eyes</i>&mdash;have
      melted the steel that was driven into my heart long ago, his voice and the
      touch of his hand have gently checked my bitterest thoughts. Are you
      listening?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You ask what I have done to him. It is nothing in comparison to what he
      would have done to me. It isn't necessary to explain. You know the thing
      he has had in his heart to do. I have known it from the beginning. It is
      the treacherous heart of his mother that propels that boy's blood along
      its craven way. She was an evil thing&mdash;as evil as God ever put life
      into.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Go on.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I loved her as no woman was ever loved before&mdash;or since. I thought she
      loved me; I believe she did. He&mdash;Frederic had her portrait up there
      to flash in my face. She was beautiful; she was as lovely as&mdash;but no
      more! I was not the man. She loved another. You may have guessed, as
      others have guessed, that she betrayed me. Her lover was that boy's
      father.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Dead silence reigned in the room, save for the heavy breathing of the man.
      Yvonne was as still as death itself. Her hands were clenched against her
      breast.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That was years ago,&rdquo; resumed the man hoarsely.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You&mdash;you told him this?&rdquo; she cried, aghast.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He stood before me up there and said that he hoped he might some day
      discover that he was not my son.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You told him <i>then?</i>&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He cursed me for having driven his mother out of my house.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You told him?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He uttered the hope that she might come back from the grave to torture me
      for ever&mdash;to pay me back for what I had done to her.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Then you told him!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He said she must have loathed me as no man was ever loathed before. Then
      I told him.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You told him because you knew she did <i>not</i> loathe you!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yvonne! You are laughing!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I laugh because after he had said all these bitter things to you, and you
      had paid him back by telling him that he was not your son, it was you&mdash;not
      he&mdash;who was sorry!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I did not expect sympathy from you, but&mdash;to have you laugh in my
      face! I&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Did you expect sympathy from him?&rdquo; she cried.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I told him in the end that as he was not my son he need feel no
      compunction in trying to steal my wife away from me. I&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And what did he say to that?&rdquo; she broke in shrilly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nothing! He did not speak to me after that. Not one word!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nor should I speak to you again, James Brood!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yvonne&mdash;I&mdash;I love you. I&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And you loved Matilde&mdash;God pity your poor soul! For no more than I
      have done, you drove her out of your house. You accuse me in your heart
      when you vent your rage on that poor boy. Oh, I know! You suspect <i>me!</i>
      And you suspected the other one. I swear to you that you have more cause
      to suspect me than Matilde. She was not untrue to you. She could not have
      loved anyone else but you. I know&mdash;I know! Don't come near me! Not
      now! I tell you that Frederic is your son. I tell you that Matilde loved
      no one but you. You drove her out. You drive Frederic out. <i>And you will
      drive me out!</i>&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She stood over him like an accusing angel, her arms extended. He shrank
      back, glaring.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Why do you say these things to me? You cannot know&mdash;you have no
      right to say&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I <i>am</i> sorry for you, James Brood,&rdquo; she murmured, suddenly relaxing.
      Her body swayed against the table, and then she sank limply into the chair
      alongside.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yvonne!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You will never forget that you struck a man who was asleep, absolutely
      asleep, James Brood. That's why I am sorry for you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Asleep!&rdquo; he murmured, putting his hand to his eyes. &ldquo;Yes, yes&mdash;he
      was asleep! Yvonne, I&mdash;I have never been so near to loving him as I
      am now. I&mdash;I&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am going up to him. Don't try to stop me. But first let me ask you a
      question. What did Frederic say when you told him his mother was was what
      you claim?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Brood lowered his head.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He said that I was a cowardly liar.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And it was then that you began to feel that you loved him. Ah, I see what
      it is that you need, James. You are a great, strong man, a wonderful man
      in spite of all this. You have a heart&mdash;a heart that still needs
      breaking before you can ever hope to be happy.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;As if my heart hasn't already been broken,&rdquo; he groaned.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Your head has been hurt, that's all. There is a vast difference. Are you
      going out?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He looked at her in dull amazement. Slowly he began to pull himself
      together.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes. I think you should go to him. I&mdash;I gave him an hour to&mdash;to&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;To get out?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes. He must go, you see. See him, if you will. I shall not oppose you.
      Find out what he expects to do.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She passed swiftly by him as he started toward the door. In the hall,
      which was bright with the sunlight from the upper windows, she turned to
      face him. To his astonishment her cheeks were aglow and her eyes bright
      with eagerness. She seemed almost radiant.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes; it needs breaking, James,&rdquo; she said, and went up the stairs, leaving
      him standing there dumbfounded. Near the top she began to hum a blithe
      tune. It came down to him distinctly&mdash;the weird little air that had
      haunted him for years&mdash;Feverelli's!
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <a name="link2HCH0018" id="link2HCH0018"> </a>
    </p>
    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER XVIII
    </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">T</span>o Brood's surprise
      she came half-way down the steps again, and, leaning over the
      railing, spoke to him with a voice full of irony.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Will you be good enough to call off your spy, James?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What do you mean?&rdquo; He had started to put on his light overcoat.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I think you know,&rdquo; she said briefly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Do you consider me so mean, so infamous as&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo; he began
      hotly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nevertheless, I feel happier when I know he is out of the house. Call off
      your dog, James.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He smothered an execration and then called out harshly to Jones:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ask Ranjab to attend me here, Jones. He is to go out with me,&rdquo; he said to
      the butler a moment later.
    </p>
    <p>
      Yvonne was still leaning over the banister, a scornful smile on her lips.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I shall wait until you are gone. I intend to see Frederic alone,&rdquo; she
      said, with marked emphasis on the final word.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;As you like,&rdquo; said he coldly.
    </p>
    <p>
      She crossed the upper hall and disappeared from view down the corridor
      leading to her own room. Her lips were set with decision; a wild, reckless
      light filled her eyes, and the smile of scorn had given way to one of
      exaltation. Her breath came fast and tremulously through quivering
      nostrils as she closed her door and hurried across to the little
      vine-covered balcony.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The time has come&mdash;the time has come, thank God!&rdquo; she was saying to
      herself, over and over again. The French doors stuck. She was jerking
      angrily at them when her maid hurried in from the bedroom, attracted by
      the unusual commotion.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;<i>Que faites vous, madame?</i>&rdquo; she cried anxiously.
    </p>
    <p>
      Her mistress turned quickly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Listen! Go downstairs at once and tell them that I have dismissed you. At
      once, do you hear?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;<i>Oui madame!</i>&rdquo; cried Cleste, her eyes dancing with a sudden,
      incomprehensible delight.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You are to leave the house immediately. I dismiss you. You have been
      stealing from me, do you understand?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;<i>Oui, madame. Je comprendes parfaitement, madame!</i>&rdquo; cried the maid,
      actually clapping her hands.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You will pack two steamer-trunks and get them out of the house before
      five o'clock. You are going back to Paris. You are dismissed.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The little Frenchwoman beamed.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;<i>Certainement, madame! Par le premier bateau. Je comprend</i>.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The first boat for Havre&mdash;do you know the hour for sailing? Consult
      the morning paper, Cleste.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;<i>En bien, madame. La Provence. Il part demain. Je&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;</i>&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Go at once!&rdquo; cried the mistress, waving her hands excitedly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;<i>Vous me renvoyez!</i>&rdquo; And the little maid dashed out of the room.
    </p>
    <p>
      As she descended the back stairs an amazing change came over her. Her
      sprightly face became black with sullen rage and her eyes snapped with
      fury. So violent was her manner when she accosted Jones in the servants'
      hall that he fell back in some alarm. She was not long in making him
      understand that she had been dismissed, however, and that she would surely
      poison the diabolical creature upstairs if she remained in the house
      another hour. Even the cook, who had a temper of her own, was appalled by
      the exhibition; other servants were struck dumb.
    </p>
    <p>
      Jones, perspiring freely, said something about calling in an officer, and
      then Cleste began to weep bitterly. All she wanted was to get out of the
      house before she did something desperate to the cruel tyrant upstairs, and
      she'd be eternally grateful to Jones if he'd get her trunks out of the
      storeroom as soon as&mdash;&mdash;&mdash; But Jones was already on his way
      to give instructions to the furnace-man.
    </p>
    <p>
      Cleste took the occasion to go into hysterics, and the entire servant
      body fell to work hissing &ldquo;<i>Sh&mdash;h!</i>&rdquo; in an agony of apprehension
      lest the turmoil should penetrate the walls and reach the ears of the
      &ldquo;woman upstairs.&rdquo; They closed all of the doors and most of the windows,
      and the upstairs maid thought it would be a good idea to put a blanket
      over the girl's head.
    </p>
    <p>
      Left alone, Yvonne turned her attention to the window across the court and
      two floors above her the heavily curtained window in Brood's &ldquo;retreat.&rdquo;
       There was no sign of life there, so she hurried to the front of the house
      to wait for the departure of James Brood and his man. The two were going
      down the front steps. At the bottom Brood spoke to Ranjab, and the latter,
      as imperturbable as a rock, bowed low and moved off in an opposite
      direction to that taken by his master. She watched until both were out of
      sight. Then she rapidly mounted the stairs to the top floor.
    </p>
    <p>
      Frederic was lying on the couch near the jade room door. She was able to
      distinguish his long, dark figure after peering intently about the shadowy
      interior in what seemed at first to be a vain search for him. She shrank
      back, her eyes fixed in horror upon the prostrate shadow. Suddenly he
      stirred and then half raised himself on one elbow to stare at the figure
      in the doorway.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Is it <i>you?</i>&rdquo; he whispered hoarsely, and dropped back with a great
      sigh on his lips.
    </p>
    <p>
      Her heart leaped. The blood rushed back to her face. Quickly closing the
      door, she advanced into the room, her tread as swift and as soft as a
      cat's.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He has gone out. We are quite alone,&rdquo; she said, stopping to lean against
      the table, suddenly faint with excitement.
    </p>
    <p>
      He laughed, a bitter, mirthless, snarling laugh.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Get up, Frederic. Be a man! I know what has happened. Get up! I want to
      talk it over with you. We must plan. We must decide now at once&mdash;before
      he returns.&rdquo; The words broke from her lips with sharp, staccato-like
      emphasis.
    </p>
    <p>
      He came to a sitting posture slowly, all the while staring at her with a
      dull wonder in his heavy eyes.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Pull yourself together,&rdquo; she cried hurriedly. &ldquo;We cannot talk here. I am
      afraid in this room. It has ears, I know. That awful Hindu is always here,
      even though he may seem to be elsewhere. We will go down to my boudoir.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He slowly shook his head and then allowed his chin to sink dejectedly into
      his hands. With his elbows resting on his knees, he watched her movements
      in a state of increasing interest and bewilderment. She turned abruptly to
      the Buddha, whose placid, smirking countenance seemed to be alive to the
      situation in all of its aspects. Standing close, her hands behind her
      back, her figure very erect and theatric, she proceeded to address the
      image in a voice full of mockery.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, my chatterbox friend, I have pierced his armour, haven't I? He will
      creep up here and ask you, his wonderful god, to tell him what to do about
      it, <i>ae?</i> His wits are tangled. He doubts his senses. And when he
      comes to you, my friend, and whines his secret doubts into your excellent
      and trustworthy ear, do me the kindness to keep the secret I shall now
      whisper to you, for I trust you, too, you amiable fraud.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Standing on tiptoe, she put her lips to the idol's ear and whispered.
      Frederic, across the room, roused from his lethargy by the strange words
      and still stranger action, rose to his feet and took several steps toward
      her.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;There! Now you know everything. You know more than James Brood knows, for
      you know what his charming wife is about to do next.&rdquo; She drew back and
      regarded the image through half-closed, smouldering eyes. &ldquo;But he will
      know before long&mdash;before long.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What are you doing, Yvonne?&rdquo; demanded Frederic unsteadily.
    </p>
    <p>
      She whirled about and came toward him, her hands still clasped behind her
      back.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Come with me,&rdquo; she said, ignoring his question.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He&mdash;he thinks I am in love with you,&rdquo; said he, shaking his head.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And are you not in love with me?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He was startled. &ldquo;Good Lord, Yvonne!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She came quite close to him. He could feel the warmth that travelled from
      her body across the short space that separated them. The intoxicating
      perfume filled his nostrils; he drew a deep breath, his eyes closing
      slowly as his senses prepared to succumb to the delicious spell that came
      over him. When he opened them an instant later she was still facing him,
      as straight and fearless as a soldier, and the light of victory was in her
      dark, compelling eyes.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well,&rdquo; she said deliberately, &ldquo;I am ready to go away with you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He fell back stunned beyond the power of speech. His brain was filled with
      a thousand clattering noises.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He has turned you out,&rdquo; she went on rapidly. &ldquo;He disowns you. Very well;
      the time has come for me to exact payment of him for that and for all that
      has gone before. I shall go away with you. I&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Impossible!&rdquo; he cried, finding his tongue and drawing still farther away
      from her.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Are you not in love with me?&rdquo; she whispered softly.
    </p>
    <p>
      He put his hands to his eyes to shut out the alluring vision.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;For God's sake, Yvonne&mdash;leave me. Let me go my way. Let me&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He cursed your mother! He curses you! He damns you&mdash;as he damned
      her. You can pay him up for everything. You owe nothing to him. He has
      killed every&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Frederic straightened up suddenly and, with a loud cry of exultation,
      raised his clenched hands above his head.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;By Heaven, I will break him! I will make him pay! Do you know what he has
      done to me? Listen to this: he boasts of having reared me to manhood, as
      one might bring up a prize beast, that he might make me pay for the wrong
      that my poor mother did a quarter of a century ago. All these years he has
      had in mind this thing that he has done to-day. All my life has been spent
      in preparation for the sacrifice that came an hour ago. I have suffered
      all these years in ignorance of&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Not so loud!&rdquo; she whispered, alarmed by the vehemence of his reawakened
      fury.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, I'm not afraid!&rdquo; he cried savagely. &ldquo;Can you imagine anything more
      diabolical than the scheme he has had in mind all these years? To pay back
      my mother&mdash;whom he loved and still loves&mdash;yes, by Heaven, he
      still loves her&mdash;he works to this beastly end! He made her suffer the
      agonies of the damned up to the day of her death by refusing her the right
      to have the child that he swears is no child of his. Oh, you don't know
      the story&mdash;you don't know the kind of man you have for a husband&mdash;you
      don't&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, yes; I do know!&rdquo; she cried violently, beating her breast with
      clenched hands. &ldquo;I <i>do</i> know! I know that he still loves the poor
      girl who went out of this house with his curses ringing in her ears a
      score of years ago, and who died still hearing them. And I had almost come
      to the point of pitying him&mdash;I was failing&mdash;I was weakening. He
      is a wonderful man. I&mdash;I was losing myself. But that is all over.
      Three months ago I could have left him without a pang&mdash;yesterday I
      was afraid that it would never be possible. To-day he makes it easy for
      me. He has hurt you beyond all reason, not because he hates you, but
      because he loved your mother.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But you do love him!&rdquo; cried Frederic in stark wonder. &ldquo;You don't care the
      snap of your fingers for me. What is all this you are saying, Yvonne? You
      must be mad. Think! Think what you are saying.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I have thought&mdash;I am always thinking. I know my own mind well
      enough. It is settled: I am going away, and I am going with you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You can't be in earnest!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am desperately in earnest. You owe nothing to him now. He says you are
      not his son. You owe nothing but hatred to him, and you should pay. You
      owe vengeance for your mother's sake&mdash;for the sake of her whose face you
      have come to love, who loved you to the day she died, I am sure. He will
      proclaim to the world that you are not his son, he will brand you with the
      mark of shame, he will drive you out of New York. You are the son of a
      music-master, he shouts from the housetops! Your mother was a vile woman,
      he shouts from the housetops! You cannot remain here. You <i>must</i> go.
      You must take me with you. Ah, you are thinking of Lydia! Well, are you
      thinking of dragging her through the mire that he will create? Are you
      willing to give her the name he declares is not yours to give? Are you a
      craven, whipped coward who will not strike back when the chance is offered
      to give a blow that will&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I cannot listen to you, Yvonne!&rdquo; cried Frederic, aghast. His heart was
      pounding so fiercely that the blood surged to his head in great waves,
      almost stunning him with its velocity.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We go to-morrow!&rdquo; she cried out in an ecstasy of triumph. She was
      convinced that he would go! &ldquo;La Provence!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Good Heaven!&rdquo; he gasped, dropping suddenly into a chair and burying his
      face in his shaking hands. &ldquo;What will this mean to Lydia&mdash;what will she do&mdash;what
      will become of her?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      A quiver of pain crossed the woman's face, her eyelids fell as if to shut
      out something that shamed her in spite of all her vainglorious
      protestations. Then the spirit of exaltation resumed its sway. She lifted
      her eyes heavenward, and inaudible words trembled on her lips. A moment
      later she stood over him, her hands extended as if in blessing.
    </p>
    <p>
      Had he looked up at that instant he would have witnessed a Yvonne he did
      not know. No longer was she the alluring, sensuous creature who had been
      in his thoughts for months, but a transfigured being whose soul looked out
      through gentle, pitying eyes, whose wiles no longer were employed in the
      devices of which she was past-mistress, whose real nature was revealed now
      for the first time since she entered the house of James Brood.
    </p>
    <p>
      There was pain and suffering in the lovely eyes, and there was a strange
      atmosphere of sanctuary attending the very conquest she had made. But
      Frederic did not look up until all this had passed and the smile of
      triumph was on her lips again and the glint of determination in her eyes.
      He had missed the revelation that would have altered his estimate of her
      for the future.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You cannot marry Lydia now,&rdquo; she said, affecting a sharpness of tone that
      caused him to shrink involuntarily. &ldquo;It is your duty to write her a letter
      to-night, explaining all that has happened to-day. She would sacrifice
      herself for you to-day, but there is&mdash;to-morrow! A thousand
      to-morrows, Frederic. Don't forget them, my dear. They would be ugly,
      after all, and she is too good, too fine to be dragged into&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You are right!&rdquo; he exclaimed, leaping to his feet. &ldquo;It would be the
      vilest act that a man could perpetrate. Why&mdash;why, it would be proof
      of what he says of me&mdash;it would stamp me for ever the dastard he&mdash;no,
      no; I could never lift my head again if I were to do this utterly vile
      thing to Lydia. He said to me here&mdash;not an hour ago&mdash;that he
      expected me to go ahead and blight that loyal girl's life, that I would
      consider it a noble means of self-justification! What do you think of
      that? He&mdash;&mdash;&mdash; But wait! What is this that we are proposing
      to do? Give me time to think! Why&mdash;why, I can't take you away from him,
      Yvonne! What am I thinking of? Have I no sense of honour? Am I&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You are not his son,&rdquo; she said significantly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But that is no reason why I should stoop to a foul trick like this. Do&mdash;do
      you know what you are suggesting?&rdquo; He drew back from her with a look of
      disgust in his eyes. &ldquo;No! I'm not that vile! I&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Frederic, you must let me&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I don't want to hear anything more, Yvonne. What manner of woman are you?
      He is your husband, he loves you, he trusts you; oh, yes, he does! And you
      would leave him like this? You would&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Hush! Not so loud!&rdquo; she cried in great agitation.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And let me tell you something more. Although I can never marry Lydia, by
      Heaven, I shall love her to the end of my life. I will not betray that
      love. To the end of time she shall know that my love for her is real and
      true and&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Frederic, you must listen to me,&rdquo; she cried, wringing her hands. &ldquo;You
      must hear what I have to say to you. Wait! Do not leave me!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What is it, Yvonne&mdash;what is it?&rdquo; he cried, pausing in utter
      amazement after taking a few steps toward the door.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Where are you going?&rdquo; she whispered, following him with dragging steps.
      &ldquo;Not to <i>him?</i>&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Certainly not! Do you think I would betray you to him?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Wait! Give me time to think,&rdquo; she pleaded. He shook his head resolutely.
      &ldquo;Do not judge me too harshly. Hear what I have to say before you condemn
      me. I am not the vile creature you think, Frederic. Wait! Let me think!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He stared at her for a moment in deep perplexity and then slowly drew
      near.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yvonne, I do not believe you mean to do wrong&mdash;I do not believe it
      of you. You have been carried away by some horrible&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Listen to me,&rdquo; she broke in fiercely. &ldquo;I would have sacrificed you&mdash;aye,
      sacrificed you, poor boy&mdash;in order to strike James Brood the
      cruellest blow that man ever sustained. I would have destroyed you in
      destroying him&mdash;God forgive me! But you have shown me how terrible I
      am, how utterly terrible! Love you? No! No! Not in that way. I would have
      put a curse, an undeserved curse, upon your innocent head, and all for the
      joy it would give me to see James Brood grovel in misery for the rest of
      his life. Oh!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She uttered a groan of despair and self-loathing so deep and full of pain
      that his heart was chilled.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yvonne!&rdquo; he gasped, dumbfounded.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Do not come near me!&rdquo; she cried out, covering her face with her hands.
      For a full minute she stood before him, straight and rigid as a statue, a
      tragic figure he was never to forget. Suddenly she lowered her hands. To
      his surprise, a smile was on her lips.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You would never have gone away with me. I know it now. All these months I
      have been counting on you for this very hour, this culminating hour&mdash;and
      now I realise how little hope I have really had, even from the beginning.
      You are honourable. There have been times when my influence over you was
      such that you resisted only because you were loyal to yourself&mdash;not
      to Lydia, not to my husband&mdash;but to yourself. I came to this house
      with but one purpose in mind. I came here to take you away from the man
      who has always stood as your father. I would not have become your mistress&mdash;pah!
      how loathsome it sounds!&mdash;but I would have enticed you away, believing
      myself to be justified. I would have struck James Brood that blow. He
      would have gone to his grave believing himself to have been paid in full
      by the son of the woman he had degraded, by the boy he had reared for the
      slaughter, by the blood&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;In God's name, Yvonne, what is this you are saying? What have you against
      my&mdash;against him?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Wait! I shall come to that. I did not stop to consider all that I should
      have to overcome. First, there was your soul, your honour, your integrity
      to consider. I did not think of all those things. I did not stop to think
      of the damnable wrong I should be doing to you. I was blind to everything
      except my one great, long-enduring purpose. I could see nothing else but
      triumph over James Brood. To gain my end it was necessary that I should be
      his wife. I became his wife&mdash;I deliberately took that step in order
      to make complete my triumph over him. I became the wife of the man I had
      hated with all my soul, Frederic. So you can see how far I was willing to
      go to&mdash;ah, it was a hard thing to do! But I did not shrink. I went
      into it without faltering, without a single thought of the cost to myself.
      He was to pay for all that, too, in the end. Look into my eyes, Frederic.
      I want to ask you a question. Will you go away with me? Will you take me?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He returned her look steadily.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That is all I want to hear you say. It means the end. I have done all
      that could be done, and I have failed. Thank God, I have failed!&rdquo; She came
      swiftly to him and, before he was aware of her intention, clutched his
      hand and pressed it to her lips. He was shocked to find that a sudden gush
      of tears was wetting his hand.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, Yvonne!&rdquo; he cried miserably.
    </p>
    <p>
      She was sobbing convulsively. He looked down upon her dark, bowed head and
      again felt the mastering desire to crush her slender, beautiful body in
      his arms. The spell of her was upon him again, but now he realised that
      the appeal was to his spirit and not to his flesh&mdash;as it had been all
      along, he was beginning to suspect.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Don't pity me,&rdquo; she choked out. &ldquo;This will pass, as everything else has
      passed. I am proud of you now, Frederic. You are splendid. Not many men
      could have resisted in this hour of despair. You have been cast off,
      despised, degraded, humiliated. You were offered the means to retaliate.
      You&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And I was tempted!&rdquo; he cried bitterly. &ldquo;For the moment I was&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And now what is to become of <i>me?</i>&rdquo; she wailed.
    </p>
    <p>
      His heart grew cold.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You&mdash;you will leave him? You will go back to Paris? Yvonne, it will
      be a blow to him. He has had one fearful slash in the back. This will
      break him.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;At least, I may have that consolation,&rdquo; she cried, straightening up in an
      effort to revive her waning purpose. &ldquo;Yes, I shall go. I cannot stay here
      now. I&mdash;&rdquo; She paused and shuddered.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What, in Heaven's name, have you against my&mdash;against him? What does
      it all mean? How you must have hated him to&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Hated him? Oh, how feeble the word is! Hate! There should be a word that
      strikes more terror to the soul than that one. But wait! You shall know
      everything. You shall have the story from the beginning. There is much to
      tell, and there will be consolation&mdash;aye, triumph for you in the
      story I shall tell. First, let me say this to you: when I came here I did
      not know that there was a Lydia Desmond. I would have hurt that poor girl;
      but it would not have been a lasting pain. In my plans, after I came to
      know her, there grew a beautiful alternative through which she should know
      great happiness. Oh, I have planned well and carefully, but I was
      ruthless. I would have crushed her with him rather than to have failed.
      But it is all a dream that has passed, and I am awake.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It was the most cruel, but the most magnificent dream&mdash;ah, but I
      dare not think of it. As I stand here before you now, Frederic, I am shorn
      of all my power. I could not strike him as I might have done a month ago.
      Even as I was cursing him but a moment ago I realised that I could not
      have gone on with the game. Even as I begged you to take your revenge, I
      knew that it was not myself who urged, but the thing that was having its
      death-struggle within me.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Go on. Tell me. Why do you stop?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She was glancing fearfully toward the Hindu's door. &ldquo;There is one man in
      this house who knows. He reads my every thought. He does not know all, but
      he knows <i>me</i>. He has known from the beginning that I was not to be
      trusted. That man is never out of my thoughts. I fear him, Frederic&mdash;I
      fear him as I fear death. If he had not been here I&mdash;I believe I
      should have dared anything. I <i>could</i> have taken you away with me
      months ago. But he worked his spell and I was afraid. I faltered. He knew
      that I was afraid, for he spoke to me one day of the beautiful serpents in
      his land that were cowards in spite of the death they could deal with one
      flash of their fangs. You were intoxicated. I <i>am</i> a thing of beauty.
      I can charm as the&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;God knows that is true,&rdquo; he said hoarsely.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But enough of that! I am stricken with my own poison. Go to the door! See
      if he is there. I fear&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No one is near,&rdquo; said he, after striding swiftly to both doors, listening
      at one and peering out through the other.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You will have to go away, Frederic. I shall have to go. But we shall not
      go together. In my room I have kept hidden the sum of ten thousand
      dollars, waiting for the day to come when I should use it to complete the
      game I have played. I knew that you would have no money of your own. I was
      prepared even for that. Look again! See if anyone is there? I feel&mdash;I
      feel that someone is near us. Look, I say!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He obeyed.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;See! There is no one near.&rdquo; He held open the door to the hall. &ldquo;You must
      speak quickly. I am to leave this house in an hour. I was given the
      hour.&rdquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ah, I can see by your face that you hate him! It is well. That is
      something. It is but little, I know, after all I have wished for&mdash;but
      it is something for me to treasure&mdash;something for me to take back
      with me to the one sacred little spot in this beastly world of men and
      women.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yvonne, you are the most incomprehensible&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Am I not beautiful, Frederic? Tell me!&rdquo; She came quite close to him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You are the most beautiful woman in all the world,&rdquo; he said abjectly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And I have wasted all my beauty&mdash;I have lent it to unloveliness, and
      it has not been destroyed! It is still with me, is it not? I have not lost
      it in&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You are beautiful beyond words&mdash;beyond anything I have ever
      imagined,&rdquo; said he, suddenly passing his hand over his brow.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You would have loved me if it had not been for Lydia?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I couldn't have helped myself. I&mdash;I fear I&mdash;faltered in my&mdash;are
      you still trying to tempt me? Are you still asking me to go away with
      you?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      A hoarse cry came from the doorway behind them&mdash;a cry of pain and
      anger that struck terror to their souls.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <a name="link2HCH0019" id="link2HCH0019"> </a>
    </p>
